{"title_page": "Bulbul Shah", "text_new": "{{short description|14th c. Sufi missionary to Kashmir}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| honorific-prefix =BulBul Shah \n| name             = Syed Sharf u dinn Abdul Rehman Shah \n| honorific-suffix = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = Hazrat_Bul_Bul_Shah.png\n| caption          = The first Sufi saint who reached Kashmir, during the time of Rinchin Shah, was Sayed Sharafuddin Bulbul Shah from Turkey\n| religion         = Islam\n| founder          =\n| philosophy       = Missionary Islam \n| known_for        = Islamic Missionary\n| home_town        = Turkey\n| background       = green\n}}\n\n'''Bulbul Shah''' (Arabic Script: \u0628\u0644\u0628\u0644 \u0634\u0627\u0647 ) was a 14th-century Turkistani Sufi of Suhrawardi order.He introduced [[Sufism|Islam]] to [[Kashmir]] by inviting and converting the King of Kashmir, [[Rinchan]] Shah to Islam.<ref>{{cite book |last=Naseem |first=Hamid |year=2001 |title=Muslim Philosophy: Science and Mysticism |publisher=Sarup & Sons |page=325 |isbn=9788176252300}}</ref> He was from a Suhrawardi order and his mentor was Mir Syed Niymatullah who ordered him to on take islamic missionary movement to Kashmir.He first came to Kashmir in 1286,secondly in 1320 with a expeditionaries counting to about 1000.Shah was mentioned by Baba Dawood Mishkati in ''Asrar-ul- Abrar'' and Rafi-ud- Din ''Nawadir-ul- Akhbar.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.greaterkashmir.com/news/opinion/profiling-bulbul-shah/165273.htm|title=Profiling Bulbul Shah|last=|author=Dr. Farooq Ahmad Peer|date=6 March 2014|accessdate=19 March 2019|publisher=[[Greater Kashmir]]|quote=The preacher among the preachers of Islam in Kashmir is believed to be Hazrat Syed Sharaf-ud- DIN Abdul Rahman (RA), popularly known as Syed Bulbul Shah (RA). He is believed to have touched the threshold of Kashmir during the reign of Suhadeva (1301-20).}}</ref>\n\n== Shrine ==\nA shrine is dedicated to his burial place on the [[Jhelum River|Jhelum river]] which was actually a Langar , a community kitchen.In 2011 [[Archaeological Survey of India|Archeological Survey of India]] (ASI) rejected the proposal to make it a National Monument even after the High Court ordered the Survey to accept it. Petitioner GA Lone filed a contempt petition against the official respondents. The High Court directed the [[Jammu and Kashmir]] Chief Secretary, Director, Archives and others to file a compliance report.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2013/20130707/kashmir.htm#1|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India \u2013 KASHMIR TRIBUNE|website=www.tribuneindia.com|access-date=2019-01-18}}</ref>\n[[File:Bulbul shah.jpg|thumb|270.99x270.99px|Pictures of The Shrine of BulBul Shah]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cite journal|last=Hasan|first=Mohibbul|date=2012-04-24|title=Bulbul S\u0332h\u0332\u0101h|url=https://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/bulbul-shah-SIM_8427|journal=Encyclopaedia of Islam, Second Edition|language=en|ref=harv}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Turkish Sufis]]\n[[Category:Muslim missionaries]]\n[[Category:History of Kashmir]]\n[[Category:14th-century Muslims]]\n\n\n{{Sufi-stub}}\n{{Asia-reli-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|14th c. Sufi missionary to Kashmir}}\n{{Infobox religious biography\n| honorific-prefix =BulBul Shah \n| name             = Syed Sharf u dinn Abdul Rehman Shah \n| honorific-suffix = \n| native_name      = \n| native_name_lang = \n| image            = Hazrat_Bul_Bul_Shah.png\n| caption          = The first Sufi saint who reached Kashmir, during the time of Rinchin Shah, was Sayed Sharafuddin Bulbul Shah from Turkey\n| religion         = Islam\n| founder          =\n| philosophy       = Missionary Islam \n| known_for        = Islamic Missionary\n| home_town        = Turkey\n| background       = green\n}}\n\n'''Bulbul Shah''' (Arabic Script: \u0628\u0644\u0628\u0644 \u0634\u0627\u0647 ) was a 14th-century Turkistani Sufi of Suhrawardi order.He introduced [[Sufism|Islam]] to [[Kashmir]] by inviting and converting the King of Kashmir, [[Rinchan]] Shah to Islam.<ref>{{cite book |last=Naseem |first=Hamid |year=2001 |title=Muslim Philosophy: Science and Mysticism |publisher=Sarup & Sons |page=325 |isbn=9788176252300}}</ref>He was from a Suhrawardi order and his mentor was Mir Syed Niymatullah who ordered him to on take islamic missionary movement to Kashmir.He first came to Kashmir in 1286,secondly in 1320 with a expeditionaries counting to about 1000.Shah was mentioned by Baba Dawood Mishkati in ''Asrar-ul- Abrar'' and Rafi-ud- Din ''Nawadir-ul- Akhbar.''<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.greaterkashmir.com/news/opinion/profiling-bulbul-shah/165273.htm|title=Profiling Bulbul Shah|last=|author=Dr. Farooq Ahmad Peer|date=6 March 2014|accessdate=19 March 2019|publisher=[[Greater Kashmir]]|quote=The preacher among the preachers of Islam in Kashmir is believed to be Hazrat Syed Sharaf-ud- DIN Abdul Rahman (RA), popularly known as Syed Bulbul Shah (RA). He is believed to have touched the threshold of Kashmir during the reign of Suhadeva (1301-20).}}</ref>\n\n== Shrine ==\nA shrine is dedicated to his burial place on the [[Jhelum River|Jhelum river]] which was actually a Langar , a community kitchen.In 2011 [[Archaeological Survey of India|Archeological Survey of India]] (ASI) rejected the proposal to make it a National Monument even after the High Court ordered the Survey to accept it. Petitioner GA Lone filed a contempt petition against the official respondents. The High Court directed the [[Jammu and Kashmir]] Chief Secretary, Director, Archives and others to file a compliance report.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/2013/20130707/kashmir.htm#1|title=The Tribune, Chandigarh, India \u2013 KASHMIR TRIBUNE|website=www.tribuneindia.com|access-date=2019-01-18}}</ref>\n[[File:Bulbul shah.jpg|thumb|270.99x270.99px|Pictures of The Shrine of BulBul Shah]]\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Cite journal|last=Hasan|first=Mohibbul|date=2012-04-24|title=Bulbul S\u0332h\u0332\u0101h|url=https://referenceworks.brillonline.com/entries/encyclopaedia-of-islam-2/bulbul-shah-SIM_8427|journal=Encyclopaedia of Islam, Second Edition|language=en|ref=harv}}\n\n[[Category:Turkish Sufis]]\n[[Category:Muslim missionaries]]\n[[Category:History of Kashmir]]\n[[Category:14th-century Muslims]]\n{{Sufi-stub}}\n{{Asia-reli-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bulbul_Shah"}
{"title_page": "Boulbaba", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=July 2007}}\n\n'''Sidi Bulbaba''', one of the earliest missionaries of [[Islam]], is honored in [[Gab\u00e8s]], [[Tunisia]] with a shrine, museum and mosque. (\"Sidi\" is comparable to \"Saint\")\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bulbaba}}\n[[Category:Muslim missionaries]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n\n\n{{Islam-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=July 2007}}\n\n'''Sidi Bulbaba''', one of the earliest missionaries of [[Islam]], is honored in [[Gab\u00e8s]], [[Tunisia]] with a shrine, museum and mosque. (\"Sidi\" is comparable to \"Saint\")\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bulbaba}}\n[[Category:Muslim missionaries]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing]]\n\n\n{{Islam-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Boulbaba"}
{"title_page": "Russian Easter Festival Overture", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Russian Easter Festival Overture''\n| subtitle            = ''Overture on Liturgical Themes''\n| type                = \n| composer            = {{nowrap|[[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]]}}\n| image               = Rimsky-Korsakov Repin crop.png\n| image_upright       = 1.1\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = The composer in 1893, portrayed by [[Ilya Repin]]\n| native_name         = {{lang-ru|\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043b\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a|italic=yes}}\n| key                 = \n| catalogue           = [[Opus number|Op.]] 36\n| dedication          = memories of [[Modest Mussorgsky]] and [[Alexander Borodin]]\n| based_on            = \n| composed            = {{start date|1887}}\u201388\n| performed           = {{start date|1888|12}}\n| published           = \n| movements           = \n| scoring             = orchestra\n}}\n{{Listen|type=music\n| filename     = Rimsky-Korsakov, Russian Easter Festival Overture, Op. 36.ogg\n| title        = ''Russian Easter Festival Overture'' (15:35)\n| description  = Courtesy of [[Musopen]]. Performed by the [[Czech National Symphony Orchestra]]\n}}\n'''''Russian Easter Festival Overture: Overture on Liturgical Themes''''' ({{lang|ru|'''\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043b\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a'''}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Svetliy prazdnik}}), [[Opus number|Op.]] 36, also known as the '''''Great Russian Easter Overture''''', is a [[concert overture]] written by the Russian composer [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]] between August 1887 and April 1888. It was dedicated to the memories of [[Modest Mussorgsky]] and [[Alexander Borodin]], two members of the group of composers known in English as \"[[The Five (composers)|The Five]]\". It is the last of what many call his three most exceptionally brilliant orchestral works, preceded by ''[[Capriccio Espagnol]]'' and ''[[Scheherazade (Rimsky-Korsakov)|Scheherazade]]''. The work received its premiere at a Russian symphony concert in St. Petersburg in late December 1888.\n\n==Instrumentation==\nThe overture is scored for a [[Romance (music)|Romantic]] orchestra, consisting of 3 [[flute]]s (1 doubling [[piccolo]]), 2 [[oboe]]s, 2 [[clarinet]]s in C, 2 [[bassoon]]s, 4 [[French horn|horns]] in F, 2 [[trumpet]]s in B{{music|flat}}, 3 [[trombone]]s, [[tuba]], 3 [[timpani]] tuned to A, D and G, percussion ([[glockenspiel]], [[triangle (musical instrument)|triangle]], [[cymbal]]s, [[bass drum]], [[tam-tam]]), [[harp]], and [[string section|strings]].\n\n==Background==\n{{refimprove|section|date=January 2017}}\nThe score is prefaced by two quotations from the [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament|New Testaments]] and a third, written by the composer; these correspond to each of the overture's three parts. The first part is prefaced by two verses from [[Psalm 68|Psalm 68:1\u20132]]; the second from the [[Gospel of Mark]] 16:1\u20136; and a third by a description of the Easter celebration written by the composer.\n\nThe melodies in the overture are largely from the [[Russian Orthodox]] [[liturgy]], based on a collection of old Russian Orthodox liturgical chants called the ''[[Obikhod]]''.\n\nRimsky-Korsakov said in his autobiography that he was eager to reproduce \"the legendary and heathen aspect of the holiday, and the transition from the solemnity and mystery of the evening of Passion Saturday to the unbridled pagan-religious celebrations of Easter Sunday morning\".{{Cite quote|date=January 2017}} He had always been interested in \u2013 and enjoyed \u2013 liturgical themes and music, though he was not a believer. \n\nAmerican musicologist [[Milo\u0161 Velimirovi\u0107]] explains, \"The Obikhod was like the Russian's Liber usualis... In 1848 it became mandatory for all of the Churches in Russia.\"{{Cite quote|date=January 2017}} Thus the Obikhod became associated with nationalism in Russia. The tunes that Rimsky chose from the Obikhod would carry a certain nationalistic and religious weight, and Russians would absolutely know them. The piece also appealed to the emotions of Russians because of its expression of the Easter Holiday, the high point of the liturgical calendar. \n\nProfessor [[Robert Greenberg]] describes the ''Russian Easter Festival Overture'' as, \"A narrative story of a Russian Easter day from dawn until dusk.\"{{Cite quote|date=January 2017}} In Russian, Easter is known as the \"Bright Holiday\".\n\n==Structure==\nThe ''Russian Easter Festival Overture'' is mainly in [[Sonata form|sonata allegro form]], with a lengthy introduction at the beginning. Throughout the piece, there are a number of prominent solo sections, featuring violin, cello, trombone, clarinet, and flute.\n\nThe opening section is written in {{music|time|5|2}} time, and is one of the more famous works for orchestra in [[quintuple meter]]. The final section of the piece is notated in {{music|time|2|1}} time, making occasional use of {{music|time|3|1}}, and is one of very few orchestral works to use either of these time signatures.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMSLP|work=Russian Easter Festival, Op.36 (Rimsky-Korsakov, Nikolay)|cname=''Russian Easter Festival Overture''}}\n* {{Internet Archive|Rimsky-korsakovRussianEasterOverture|Rimsky-Korsakov: ''Russian Easter Overture'', Op. 36 (''La Grande P\u00e2que Russe'')}}: [[Philadelphia Orchestra]], [[Eugene Ormandy]], conductor\n\n{{Easter}}\n{{Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Classical music}}\n\n{{italic title}}\n[[Category:Compositions by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]]\n[[Category:Concert overtures]]\n[[Category:1888 compositions]]\n[[Category:Easter traditions]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical composition\n| name                = ''Russian Easter Festival Overture''\n| subtitle            = ''Overture on Liturgical Themes''\n| type                = \n| composer            = {{nowrap|[[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]]}}\n| image               = Rimsky-Korsakov Repin crop.png\n| image_upright       = 1.1\n| alt                 = \n| caption             = The composer in 1893, portrayed by [[Ilya Repin]]\n| native_name         = {{lang-ru|\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043b\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a|italic=yes}}\n| key                 = \n| catalogue           = [[Opus number|Op.]] 36\n| dedication          = memories of [[Modest Mussorgsky]] and [[Alexander Borodin]]\n| based_on            = \n| composed            = {{start date|1887}}\u201388\n| performed           = {{start date|1888|12}}\n| published           = \n| movements           = \n| scoring             = orchestra\n}}\n{{Listen|type=music\n| filename     = Rimsky-Korsakov, Russian Easter Festival Overture, Op. 36.ogg\n| title        = ''Russian Easter Festival Overture'' (15:35)\n| description  = Courtesy of [[Musopen]]. Performed by the [[Czech National Symphony Orchestra]]\n}}\n'''''Russian Easter Festival Overture: Overture on Liturgical Themes''''' ({{lang|ru|'''\u0421\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043b\u044b\u0439 \u043f\u0440\u0430\u0437\u0434\u043d\u0438\u043a'''}}, {{lang|ru-Latn|Svetliy prazdnik}}), [[Opus number|Op.]] 36, also known as the '''''Great Russian Easter Overture''''', is a [[concert overture]] written by the Russian composer [[Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]] between August 1887 and April 1888. It was dedicated to the memories of [[Modest Mussorgsky]] and [[Alexander Borodin]], two members of the group of composers known in English as \"[[The Five (composers)|The Five]]\". It is the last of what many call his three most exceptionally brilliant orchestral works, preceded by ''[[Capriccio Espagnol]]'' and ''[[Scheherazade (Rimsky-Korsakov)|Scheherazade]]''. The work received its premiere at a Russian symphony concert in St. Petersburg in late December 1888.\n\n==Instrumentation==\nThe overture is scored for a [[Romantic]] orchestra, consisting of 3 [[flute]]s (1 doubling [[piccolo]]), 2 [[oboe]]s, 2 [[clarinet]]s in C, 2 [[bassoon]]s, 4 [[French horn|horns]] in F, 2 [[trumpet]]s in B{{music|flat}}, 3 [[trombone]]s, [[tuba]], 3 [[timpani]] tuned to A, D and G, percussion ([[glockenspiel]], [[triangle (musical instrument)|triangle]], [[cymbal]]s, [[bass drum]], [[tam-tam]]), [[harp]], and [[string section|strings]].\n\n==Background==\n{{refimprove|section|date=January 2017}}\nThe score is prefaced by two quotations from the [[Old Testament|Old]] and [[New Testament|New Testaments]] and a third, written by the composer; these correspond to each of the overture's three parts. The first part is prefaced by two verses from [[Psalm 68|Psalm 68:1\u20132]]; the second from the [[Gospel of Mark]] 16:1\u20136; and a third by a description of the Easter celebration written by the composer.\n\nThe melodies in the overture are largely from the [[Russian Orthodox]] [[liturgy]], based on a collection of old Russian Orthodox liturgical chants called the ''[[Obikhod]]''.\n\nRimsky-Korsakov said in his autobiography that he was eager to reproduce \"the legendary and heathen aspect of the holiday, and the transition from the solemnity and mystery of the evening of Passion Saturday to the unbridled pagan-religious celebrations of Easter Sunday morning\".{{Cite quote|date=January 2017}} He had always been interested in \u2013 and enjoyed \u2013 liturgical themes and music, though he was not a believer. \n\nAmerican musicologist [[Milo\u0161 Velimirovi\u0107]] explains, \"The Obikhod was like the Russian's Liber usualis... In 1848 it became mandatory for all of the Churches in Russia.\"{{Cite quote|date=January 2017}} Thus the Obikhod became associated with nationalism in Russia. The tunes that Rimsky chose from the Obikhod would carry a certain nationalistic and religious weight, and Russians would absolutely know them. The piece also appealed to the emotions of Russians because of its expression of the Easter Holiday, the high point of the liturgical calendar. \n\nProfessor [[Robert Greenberg]] describes the ''Russian Easter Festival Overture'' as, \"A narrative story of a Russian Easter day from dawn until dusk.\"{{Cite quote|date=January 2017}} In Russian, Easter is known as the \"Bright Holiday\".\n\n==Structure==\nThe ''Russian Easter Festival Overture'' is mainly in [[Sonata form|sonata allegro form]], with a lengthy introduction at the beginning. Throughout the piece, there are a number of prominent solo sections, featuring violin, cello, trombone, clarinet, and flute.\n\nThe opening section is written in {{music|time|5|2}} time, and is one of the more famous works for orchestra in [[quintuple meter]]. The final section of the piece is notated in {{music|time|2|1}} time, making occasional use of {{music|time|3|1}}, and is one of very few orchestral works to use either of these time signatures.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMSLP|work=Russian Easter Festival, Op.36 (Rimsky-Korsakov, Nikolay)|cname=''Russian Easter Festival Overture''}}\n* {{Internet Archive|Rimsky-korsakovRussianEasterOverture|Rimsky-Korsakov: ''Russian Easter Overture'', Op. 36 (''La Grande P\u00e2que Russe'')}}: [[Philadelphia Orchestra]], [[Eugene Ormandy]], conductor\n\n{{Easter}}\n{{Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov}}\n{{authority control}}\n{{Portal bar|Classical music}}\n\n{{italic title}}\n[[Category:Compositions by Nikolai Rimsky-Korsakov]]\n[[Category:Concert overtures]]\n[[Category:1888 compositions]]\n[[Category:Easter traditions]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInstrumentation:Fixing links to disambiguation pages, improving links, other minor cleanup tasks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russian_Easter_Festival_Overture"}
{"title_page": "Direct Action Everywhere", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=July 2019}}\n{{Advert|date=July 2019}}\n{{Globalize|article|USA|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n|name         = Direct Action Everywhere\n|logo         = Dxe logo.svg\n|logo_size    = 100\n|image        = Direct Action Everywhere protest at Whole Foods Market.jpg\n|caption      = DxE protest at a [[Whole Foods Market]] in San Francisco, July 2015\n|map          =\n|msize        = \n|mcaption     = \n|abbreviation = DxE\n|motto        = \n|formation    = 2013\n|type         = \n|status       = \n|purpose      = [[Animal rights]]\n|headquarters = [[Berkeley, California]]\n|location     = \n|region_served = \n|membership   = \n|language     =\n|leader_title = \n|leader_name  = \n|main_organ   = \n|parent_organization = \n|affiliations = \n|num_staff    = \n|num_volunteers =\n|budget       = \n|website      = {{plainlink|http://directactioneverywhere.com|directactioneverywhere.com}}\n|remarks      =\n}}\n\n'''Direct Action Everywhere''' ('''DxE''') is an international [[grassroots]] network of [[animal rights]] activists founded in 2013 in the San Francisco Bay Area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/handbook|title=Direct Action Everywhere handbook|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref> DxE activists started with disruptive protests but now also use non-violent [[direct action]] tactics to further their cause, such as [[open rescue]] of animals from factory farms.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenewjournalatyale.com/2015/03/everyday-evil/|title=Everyday Evil|last=Boodman|first=Eric|date=March 20, 2015|publisher=The New Journal|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref> Their intent is to build a movement that can eventually shift culture and change social and political institutions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailykos.com/story/2016/06/01/1532982/-Fighting-Speciesism-with-Direct-Action-Animal-Rights-Activists-DxE-Disrupt-Sanders-Oakland-Rally|title=Fighting Speciesism with Direct Action: Animal Rights Activists DxE Disrupt Sanders' Oakland Rally|last=Wilkins|first=Brett|date=May 31, 2016|publisher=Daily Kos|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref> DxE activists work to \"put an end to the commodity status of animals.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://munchies.vice.com/en/articles/why-these-vegans-are-protesting-bernie-sanders-rallies|title=Why These Vegans Are Protesting Bernie Sanders Rallies|last=Woods|first=Nick|date=March 31, 2016|publisher=Vice|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Founding===\nDxE was founded in 2013 by a handful of idiots in the San Francisco Bay Area who decided to terrorise restaurants and stores, rather than outside, which was more typical of animal rights terror demonstrations.<ref name=\"whyinside\">{{cite web |url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2014/4/8/why-dxe-brings-the-message-inside | title=Why DxE Brings the Message Inside | accessdate=August 23, 2016}}</ref> DxE co-founder [[Wayne Hsiung]] investigated slaughterhouses for ten years prior to founding DxE with the goal of scaling up [[open rescue]] and other forms of non-violent direct action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animalcharityevaluators.org/resources/conversations-and-interviews/conversation-with-wayne-hsiung-direct-action-everywhere/|title=Conversation with Wayne Hsiung, Direct Action Everywhere|accessdate=August 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDxE's first action occurred in January 2013.<ref name=firstvid>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w5wffvHafRY&x-yt-ts=1421914688&x-yt-cl=84503534 |website=YouTube |title=It Starts With You...|date=January 8, 2013|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref> Six activists demonstrated in front of a meat counter at a [[Sprouts Farmers Market]], contending that the items being sold there behind the counter were not food but \"the torment and suffering of billions of our friends in factory farms and slaughterhouses.\"<ref name=\"firstvid\" />\n\n===Growth===\nDxE continued organizing protests inside restaurants and stores, citing the [[Southern Christian Leadership Conference]] and [[ACT UP]] as influences.<ref name=ourhenhouse>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourhenhouse.org/WayneHsiungEpisode245.pdf |website=[[Our Hen House]] |title=Interview with Wayne Hsiung | date=September 20, 2014 | accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref> In August 2013, DxE   activists organized the Los Angeles side of an international multi-city protest, The Earthlings March.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailynews.com/social-affairs/20130824/animal-rights-activists-march-in-downtown-la|title=Animal Rights Activists March in Downtown LA | last=Goff|first=Kelly|date=August 24, 2013|publisher=Los Angeles Daily News|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref> Approximately 40 cities and varied activist groups participated in the march.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Enviro-Tech/Animal-activists-take-over-Tel-Avivs-Rothschild-Boulevard-324132|title=Animal Activists Take Over Tel Aviv's Rothschild Boulevard | last=Goff|first=Kelly|date=August 24, 2013|publisher=Los Angeles Daily News|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, in response to a viral video produced by [[Chipotle]] called The Scarecrow, DxE organized in-store \u201cdie-ins\u201d at three San Francisco Chipotle restaurants.<ref name=scarecrow>{{cite web|url=tps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lUtnas5ScSE |website=YouTube |title=The Scarecrow|date=September 11, 2013|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"newfrontier\">{{cite web |url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2013/10/21/the-new-frontier | title=The New Frontier | accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref> DxE argued that the ad, which advertised Chipotle\u2019s purported efforts to create a more natural and humane food system was \u201chumanewashing,\u201d which animal rights activists describe as marketing efforts intended to disguise the inherent violence of using and killing animals for food.<ref name=\"chipotlestart\">{{cite web |url=http://static1.squarespace.com/static/515cca87e4b0bca14d767b61/t/526304cfe4b0971963e4897d/1382221007692/2013.10.19+Killing+is+no+Kindness+Press+Release.pdf | title=Activists in Six Cities \"Die-In\" at Chipotle | accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref> Within a few weeks, similar demonstrations were executed in Chicago, Los Angeles, Phoenix and Philadelphia. DxE responded by creating a platform for coordinated global days of action under the \u201cIt\u2019s Not Food, It\u2019s Violence\u201d message.<ref name=\"chipotlestart\" />\n\nDxE has continued with internationally coordinated monthly days of action. In addition to Chipotle, activists have also targeted other grocery stores, restaurants, clothing stores, zoos, circuses, and labs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2015/05/24/18772659.php | title=Animal Rights Protest in San Francisco | last=Boyer|first=D.|date=May 24, 2014|publisher=Indybay|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenisthenewred.com/blog/utah-protest-prosecution/8521/ | title=BREAKING: 2 Animal Activists Facing 6 Months in Jail for Protesting on the Sidewalk | last=Potter|first=Will|date=August 20, 2015|publisher=Green Is The New Red|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Clowns-Brawl-With-Protesters-Under-Circus-Big-Top-San-Bernardino-300490891.html | title=Clowns Brawl With Protesters Under Circus Big Top in San Bernardino | last=Larkin|first=Michael|date=April 17, 2015|publisher=NBC Los Angeles|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2015/03/23/animal-rights-activists-protest-use-of-animals-in-yale-labs/ | title=Animal rights activists protest use of animals in Yale labs | last=Chua|first=Jun Yua|date=March 23, 2015|publisher=Yale Daily News|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref> The original actions were organized around the San Francisco Bay Area. By December 2014, DxE's network had grown to at least 90 cities in 20 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D4dkK3tI7X8 |website=YouTube | title=Stop the Violence - DxE December Day of Action | date=January 20, 2015 | accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDxE hosts an annual Animal Liberation Conference (ALC) for grassroots, peaceful animal rights activists.<ref name=\"plantbasednews.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.plantbasednews.org/post/arrested-held-1-million-bond-vegan-activist|title='We Were Arrested And Held On $1 Million Bond' - A Vegan Activist Speaks Out|website=www.plantbasednews.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> The ALC is a full week of talks, trainings, and socials all aimed at empowering activists.<ref name=\"plantbasednews.org\"/>\n\n===Whole Foods campaign===\nDxE selected U.S.-based natural foods grocery store [[Whole Foods Market]] as the target of the investigation because the company is allegedly \u201cactively shaping the public\u2019s view of animal agriculture with false marketing.\u201d<ref name=\"Why Whole Foods\">{{cite web|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2014/12/2/why-whole-foods | title=Why Target Whole Foods?|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe activists selected Certified Humane Whole Foods egg supplier Petaluma Farms in Petaluma, California, as the target of the initial investigation.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/09/business/direct-action-everywhere-video-of-laying-hens-raises-concerns.html|title=Animal Rights Group's Video of Hens Raises Questions, but Not Just for Farms|date=January 8, 2015|work=New York Times|accessdate=2015-01-12}}</ref> At one point, activists encountered a diseased hen who had collapsed and was struggling to breathe and removed her from the farm. They named her Mei Hua (Chinese for \u201cbeautiful flower\u201d) and made her recovery a centerpiece of the ensuing campaign and imagery.<ref name=\"Mei Hua\">{{cite web|url=http://freefromharm.org/animal-cruelty-investigation/one-survivors-story-whole-foods-humane-hoax/ | title=One Survivor's Story|date=January 15, 2015|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Petaluma Argus-Courier\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petaluma360.com/news/3374941-181/activists-targeting-petalumafarmers|title=Activists Targeting Petaluma Farmers|last=Charrier|first=Emily|date=2015-01-15|accessdate=2017-04-24}}</ref> Another farm owned by the same company was later the subject of a similar video filmed by a former employee. When asked for comment about that particular break-in after DxE's release of their initial video, the [[Sonoma County]] Sheriff's Department stated that a full investigation was underway, but that the farm appeared to be performing at \"industry standards.\"<ref name=\"Petaluma Argus-Courier\" />\n\nDxE released a 19-minute video of the investigation, \u201cTruth Matters,\u201d on YouTube and Facebook in January 2015 and received coverage in several international media outlets, including The New York Times and Mother Jones.<ref name=\"NYT\" /><ref name=\"MJ\">{{cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/tom-philpott/2015/01/you-cant-produce-eggs-industrial-scale-without-breaking-few-hens|title=What Does \"Cage Free\" Even Mean?|date=January 14, 2015|publisher=Mother Jones|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref> For several weekends following the investigation, and every month thereafter through early 2016, DxE chapters in several dozen cities organized protests inside Whole Foods stores, challenging the company\u2019s \u201cValues Matter\u201d advertising campaign.<ref name=\"Philly\">{{cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/pets/Group-to-hold-Philly-protest-against-cruel-conditions-at-humane-egg-farm-.html\n|title=Group to protest Whole Foods over egg farm conditions|date=January 10, 2015|publisher=philly.com|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NHR\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nhregister.com/article/NH/20150112/NEWS/150119864|title=Animal rights activists demonstrate at Whole Foods in Milford over egg supplier|date=January 12, 2015|publisher=New Haven Register|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref> Whole Foods announced new egg-laying standards shortly after the release of the investigation video.<ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\nOver the course of 2015, a larger team of activists investigated Diestel Turkey Ranch, one of only three companies, out of over 2,000, to achieve a 5+ rating on the 1\u20135 scale used by the Global Animal Partnership, Whole Foods\u2019s animal welfare rating scheme.<ref name=\"WaPo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/11/24/whole-foods-thanksgiving-turkeys-endure-horrific-conditions-at-calif-farm-animal-rights-activists-say/|title=Whole Foods Thanksgiving turkeys endure 'horrific conditions' at Calif. farm, activists say|date=November 24, 2015|publisher=Washington Post|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/video-shows-abuse-at-whole-foods-turkey-supplier-activists-say-1448328713|title=Video Shows Abuse at Whole Foods Turkey Supplier, Activists Say|date=November 23, 2015|publisher=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=September 20, 2015}}</ref> Activists recorded video reportedly at a Diestel-owned farm in Jamestown, CA, showing filth, overcrowding, and birds dying as infants.<ref name=\"Diestel\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=byb8WjknZxw |website=YouTube | title=Where does Whole Foods turkey really come from? | date=November 23, 2015 | accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref> Diestel added a brief mention to its website of its Jamestown farm following the investigation.<ref name=\"Diestel Website\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diestelturkey.com | title=Diestel Turkey |accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDxE released another investigation in November 2016 into Jaindl Farms, a Whole Foods farm that has supplied the White House with Thanksgiving turkeys since the 1960s rated in the 98th percentile of animal welfare according to an animal welfare audit.<ref name=\"Jaindl WaPo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/animalia/wp/2016/11/18/turkeys-supplied-to-white-house-are-raised-in-inhumane-conditions-activist-group-says/|title= Turkeys supplied to White House are raised in inhumane conditions, activist group says|date=November 18, 2016|publisher=Washington Post|accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Jaindl Website\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jaindl.com/about/ | title=Jaindl |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref> The activists released footage of birds with mutilated beaks, struggling to walk, and crowded to the point of repeated trampling.<ref name=\"Jaindl WaPo\" /> The video footage from the farm that DxE released shows birds with mangled beaks, broken legs, missing eyes, open sores and facial lesions.<ref name=\"Jaindl HuffPo\"/> In one scene, turkeys peck and nibble at a young bird\u2019s festering wound.<ref name=\"Jaindl HuffPo\"/> In another, a decaying carcass rests on the floor among live animals.<ref name=\"Jaindl HuffPo\"/> Two Huffington Post reporters visited the farm on invitation of Jaindl's owner and found that while severe injuries were uncommon, turkeys had visible sores.<ref name=\"Jaindl HuffPo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/jaindl-turkeys-white-house_us_582dbea7e4b030997bbda895|title=  The Turkey Farm That Supplies The White House Says It's Humane. See For Yourself.|date=November 22, 2016|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2018 several hundred DxE activists held a protest outside Cal Eggs Farm in Petaluma, CA, which is a supplier to Whole Foods. Some of the activists entered a barn and carried out live and diseased birds. 40 of the activists were arrested for misdemeanor trespassing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2018/05/29/animal-rights-activists-stage-huge-protest-at-petaluma-egg-farm/|title=Animal Rights Activists Stage Huge Protest At Petaluma Egg Farm|date=2018-05-29|access-date=2018-11-12|language=en}}</ref> DxE activists see \"open rescue\" as establishing \"the right to rescue\" animals legally in the future.<ref name=\"Amanda says\">{{Cite web|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2018/09/21/whole-foods-takes-legal-action-against-berkeley-animal-rights-group/|title=Whole Foods Takes Legal Action Against Berkeley Animal Rights Group|last=Amanda says|date=2018-09-21|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref>\n\nAfter numerous protests inside the Whole Foods store in Berkeley, CA, Whole Foods obtained a restraining order against DxE activists in September 2018, prohibiting Wayne Hsiung and 150 other unnamed DxE activists from entering that particular store or its parking lot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/05/whole-foods-animal-rights-protest-restraining-order|title=Whole Foods v vegans: Berkeley store gets restraining order against activists|last=Canon|first=Gabrielle|date=2018-10-05|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Liberation Pledge ===\nIn November 2015, DxE became one of the most visible backers of a new action known as the \"Liberation Pledge,\" with co-founder Wayne Hsiung authoring a piece in the ''Huffington Post'' announcing the pledge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/wayne-hsiung/post_10470_b_8480886.html|title=How Animal Lovers Are Transforming Thanksgiving|last=Hsiung|first=Wayne|date=2015-11-06|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=|access-date=2016-12-19}}</ref> According to the website liberationpledge.com, it is defined by the following three points:\n\n{{quote|One: Publicly refuse to eat animals\u2014live vegan.{{br}}\nTwo: Publicly refuse to sit where people are eating animals.{{br}}\nThree: Encourage others to take the pledge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liberationpledge.com|title=The Liberation Pledge|website=www.liberationpledge.com|access-date=2016-12-19}}</ref>}}\n\nThe pledge was considered controversial upon release, including criticisms regarding [[food justice]] concerns and by potentially isolating vegans who take the pledge.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thecommentist.com/beardedvegans14/|title=Should vegans take the Liberation Pledge? \u2013 Episode 14|last=The Bearded Vegans|date=2015-11-21|newspaper=The Commentist|language=English|access-date=2016-12-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218113347/http://thecommentist.com/beardedvegans14/|archive-date=2017-02-18|url-status=dead}}</ref> Several prominent figures in the animal rights movement, including [[Anita Krajnc case|Anita Krajnc]] of the Toronto Pig Save and [[Keith McHenry]] of [[Food Not Bombs]] took the pledge, with McHenry declaring, \"We must stop the eating of animals.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liberationpledge.com/our-words|title=Our Words \u2014 The Liberation Pledge|website=www.liberationpledge.com|access-date=2016-12-19}}</ref> Wanyama Box creator Nzinga Young defended the Liberation Pledge, writing, \"when I spend time in safe spaces with sacred people, I don\u2019t want to see carnage.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/nzinga-young/i-dont-let-my-friends-eat_b_11575264.html|title=I Don't Let Friends Eat Meat In My Presence|last=Young|first=Nzinga|date=2016-08-20|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=|access-date=2016-12-19}}</ref>\n\n===Costco campaign===\nFollowing the Farmer John investigation, DxE activists repeatedly interrupted [[LA Dodgers]] baseball games to protest the team's touting of Farmer John's \"Dodger Dogs\" hot dogs.<ref name=\"Angel Pagan EBT\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2016/10/01/angel-pagan-slam-why-the-protester-ran-on-field/|title=Angel Pagan slam: Protester speaks out on why he ran on field|last=Gafni|first=Matthias|date=2016-10-01|website=East Bay Times|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"LA Dodgers PE\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/group-807391-treatment-ingredients.html|title=DODGERS: Animal rights activists removed after running onto field during protest over hot dogs|date=2016-07-03|website=Press Enterprise|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref> Activists in LA, Colorado, and the San Francisco Bay Area jumped on the field during plays at several games with banners declaring \"Dodgers Torture Animals\" and \"Animal Liberation Now.\"<ref name=\"Angel Pagan EBT\" /><ref name=\"LA Dodgers PE\" /><ref name=\"LA Dodgers AP\">{{Cite web|url=http://gazette.com/protesters-jump-over-wall-rush-the-field-during-rockies-dodgers-game/article/1581825|title=Protesters jump over wall, rush the field during Rockies-Dodgers game|agency=Associated Press|date=2016-08-03|website=Colorado Gazette|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref> The activists tied their protests to Farmer John, protesting the promotion of \"torture and death of animals.\"<ref name=\"Angel Pagan EBT\" />\n\nDxE followed up its Farmer John investigation by investigating a cage-free egg supplier to Costco.<ref name=\"Costco NYT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/21/business/video-reveals-how-cage-free-hens-live-animal-advocates-say.html?_r=0|title=How 'Cage-Free' Hens Live, in Animal Advocates' Video|last=Strom|first=Stephanie|date=2016-10-20|website=The New York Times|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref> Costco had been a key leader in the 2016 trend of food companies committing to shift to a cage-free egg supply, but, according to DxE, the investigation raised questions about the state of animal welfare after that shift.<ref name=\"Costco Quartz\">{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/582427/after-months-of-pressure-costco-commits-to-a-cage-free-egg-supply/|title=After months of pressure, Costco commits to a cage-free egg supply|last=Shanker|first=Deena|date=2015-12-28|website=Quartz|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"Costco NYT\" />  DxE released a video that shows dead birds on the floor and injured hens pecked by other chickens. One bird had a piece of flesh hanging off its beak.<ref name=\"Strom\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/21/business/video-reveals-how-cage-free-hens-live-animal-advocates-say.html|title=How 'Cage-Free' Hens Live, in Animal Advocates' Video|last=Strom|first=Stephanie|date=2016-10-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In response to the video released by DxE, the supplier claimed that the activists had committed a \"break-in and trespassing\" and that \"The video does not show what truly goes on in our barns and appears to be staged for production effect\".<ref name=\"Costco NYT\" /> The group did not seek permission to enter the farm, Lead Organizer Wayne Hsiung said, but he argued that the group had not broken any laws because they had suspected animal cruelty and that gave them a right to enter the property.<ref name=\"Strom\"/> All birds inside the farm were destroyed due to the contamination risk the activists had introduced into the farm, according to the supplier.<ref name=\"Costco NYT\" /> The two DxE organizers who conducted the investigation were initially charged with felony commercial burglary and subsequently pleaded no-contest to a reduced charge of trespass.<ref name=\"indybay.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2019/02/19/18821286.php|title=Costco Egg Supplier Seeks to Bankrupt Animal Investigators|website=Indybay|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> The defendants were then ordered to pay restitution of $331,991 to compensate the farm owner based on his assertion that he was forced to slaughter all chickens in the barn. The defendants claim that the \"depopulated\" chickens were in a barn they never entered.<ref name=\"indybay.org\"/>\n\nDirect Action Everywhere staged a protest at the SoMa location of Costco in San Francisco. Direct Action Everywhere activists forcibly occupied the store's meat section and held a \"die-in\" near an entrance that involved activists covering each other with fake blood and pretending to eat each other. Another protest was held at a Costco store in New Berlin, Wisconsin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Armed-with-fake-blood-animal-rights-activists-10154372.php|title=Armed with fake blood, animal-rights activists protest at SF Costco|last=Johnson|first=Lizzie|date=2016-10-23|website=SF Gate|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wisconsingazette.com/2016/12/21/animal-rights-activists-protest-inside-new-berlin-costco/|title=Animal rights activists protest inside New Berlin Costco|last=Swartz|first=Tim|date=2016-12-21|website=Wisconsin Gazette|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Open rescue expansion ===\nIn December 2016, DxE open rescue projects began expanding beyond the Bay Area when members in Toronto released an investigation of a pig farm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedodo.com/baby-pig-factory-farm-2151716622.html|title=They Saw This Baby Pig And Knew They Had To Save Her Life|date=2016-12-16|work=The Dodo - For Animal People|access-date=2017-04-17|language=en}}</ref> The project was followed up by an internationally coordinated rescue with animal advocates in Sweden, Germany, and Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailycal.org/2017/03/07/animals-rescued-unsafe-farm-conditions/|title=Animals should be rescued from unsafe farm conditions|last=Cal|first=Cassie King {{!}} Special to the Daily|date=2017-03-07|website=The Daily Californian|access-date=2017-04-17}}</ref> In April 2017, DxE activists in Colorado conducted an investigation of Morning Fresh Farms, a cage-free chicken egg supplier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/NowThisPolitics/|title=NowThis Politics|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, activists with DxE entered [[Smithfield Foods]]-owned Circle Four Farms in Utah and performed an Open Rescue of two piglets subsequently named Lily and Lizzie. Their rescue triggered an extensive multi-state FBI hunt for the two baby piglets.<ref>{{cite news |last= Greenwald|first=Glenn|date=October 5, 2017 |title=The FBI's Hunt for Two Missing Piglets Reveals the Federal Cover-Up of Barbaric Factory Farms|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/10/05/factory-farms-fbi-missing-piglets-animal-rights-glenn-greenwald/|work=[[The Intercept]]|authorlink=Glenn Greenwald|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref>  DxE released a virtual-reality video that takes viewers into barns at Circle Four Farms and shows sows with bloody and mangled teats; pregnant sows gnawing on the bars of the narrow stalls they live in until they give birth; and piglets clambering over and nibbling dead siblings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/06/dining/animal-welfare-virtual-reality-video-meat-industry.html|title=Animal Welfare Groups Have a New Tool: Virtual Reality|last=Strom|first=Stephanie|date=2017-07-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> A video taken by DxE that coincided with the Open Rescue at Circle Four Farms has been called inaccurate by a spokesman for Smithfield; the video purports to show mistreatment and abuse of animals at Circle Four Farms.<ref name=\"DCSmithfield\">{{cite web|last1=Bear|first1=John|title=Animal rights organization says FBI search at Erie sanctuary related to 'rescue' of piglets from Utah|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/erie-news/ci_31305664/animal-rights-organization-says-fbi-search-at-erie|website=Boulder Daily Camera|publisher=Digital First Media|accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref> In November the same year, a group of DxE activists, which included actress [[Alexandra Paul]], claimed to expose animal cruelty and neglect at Zonneveld Dairy, a [[Land O'Lakes]] dairy supplier based in California, which included \"young calves living in filthy hutches, unprotected from record low and high temperatures between 19 and 110 degrees Fahrenheit, suffering from pneumonia, diarrhea, open sores, maggot infestations, and infections.\" The team of activists performed an Open Rescue on one sick calf, later named Roselynn.<ref>{{cite news |last=Butler|first=Kiera|date=November 7, 2017|title=Inside the Bold New Animal Liberation Movement: No Masks, No Regrets, All the Risk|url=https://www.motherjones.com/food/2017/11/inside-the-bold-new-animal-liberation-movement-no-masks-no-regrets-all-the-risk/|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|location= |access-date=November 9, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Starostinetskaya |first=Anna|date=November 8, 2017 |title=Rampant Animal Cruelty Exposed at Land O'Lakes|url=http://vegnews.com/articles/page.do?pageId=10348&catId=1|work=[[VegNews]]|location= |access-date=November 9, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn September, 2017 DxE organizers attended a small-scale poultry processing class at Long Shadow Farm, a 6-acre farm in Berthoud, Colorado specializing in pasture-raised chickens. The facility raises animals and offers \"poultry processing services.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reporterherald.com/news/larimer-county/ci_31310944/denver-animal-rights-group-says-it-rescued-chickens|title=Denver animal rights group says it 'rescued' chickens from Berthoud family farm|website=www.reporterherald.com|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> Led by DxE Organizer Aidan Cook, under the name of \"Denver Baby Animal Save\" the group entered the property masquerading as volunteers<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.reporterherald.com/news/larimer-county/ci_31310944/denver-animal-rights-group-says-it-rescued-chickens|title=Denver animal rights group says it 'rescued' chickens from Berthoud family farm|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref> and took three chickens, after asking to hold some of the birds and being assisted in doing so by the farm owners' 8 year old daughter. Opinions on the actions vary, with DxE organizers and members claiming to have \"rescued\" the birds, while the farm owners considered it \"theft\". A DxE spokesperson stated that \"even if the animal rights group could have saved more chickens by purchasing them, the group opposes buying into a system that hurts animals.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> The DxE organizers who conducted the \"open rescue\" responded to an inquiry by the farm owner, \"We have taken your birds to a sanctuary, where they can be free.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/09/19/animal-rights-group-steals-chickens-farm/680951001/|title=Animal rights group steals chickens from farm to 'free' them|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> Two of the chickens that were taken were carriers of [[Mycoplasma gallisepticum|mycoplasma]], a highly infectious respiratory disease in poultry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/09/19/animal-rights-group-steals-chickens-farm/680951001/|title=Animal rights group steals chickens from farm to 'free' them|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2017-10-18|language=en}}</ref> The Larimer County Sheriff's Office is investigating several felony allegations including trespassing, attempted theft of livestock and theft of livestock.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.coloradoan.com/story/news/2017/09/18/denver-based-animal-rights-group-steals-chickens-berthoud-farm/678055001/|title=Denver-based animal rights group steals chickens from Berthoud farm|work=Coloradoan|access-date=2017-10-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, a Utah prosecutor filed felony charges against six DxE activists stemming from an undercover investigation into conditions on a turkey farm in Moroni, Utah which serves as a supplier for [[Norbest]]. The DxE investigation found \"tens of thousands of turkeys crammed inside filthy industrial barns, virtually on top of one another.\"{{Citation needed|reason=Where is this quote from??|date=September 2019}}  The activists rescued three turkeys suffering from disease or injuries and were on the brink of death. The charges include two felony theft charges that carry possible prison terms of five years each.<ref>{{cite news |last=Greenwald |first=Glenn |date=May 4, 2018 |title=Six Animal Rights Activists Charged With Felonies for Investigation and Rescue That Led to Punishment of a Utah Turkey Farm |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/05/04/six-animal-rights-activists-charged-with-felonies-for-investigation-and-rescue-that-led-to-punishment-of-a-utah-turkey-farm/|work= The Intercept|location= |access-date=May 4, 2018 }}</ref> In October 2018 the verdict of the judge was to allow 3 of the defendants to perform community service in lieu of further punishment if they plead guilty to misdemeanors. However, Wayne Hsiung and Paul Darwin Picklesimer will have to go through an additional trial to determine the final verdict.\n\nIn April 2019, DxE activists broke into a Smithfield Foods farm in North Carolina to expose overcrowding and unsanitary conditions there, and the extensive use of antibiotics. In addition to acquiring footage of scores of sick piglets and refrigerators full of powerful antibiotics, the group took a 6 week old female pig, subsequently named Lauri, and rushed her to a vet. Testing revealed Lauri suffered from pneumonia, anemia and an antibiotic-resistant staph infection. She now resides at an animal sanctuary. Hsiung, who was involved in the raid on the farm, told ''The New York Times'' \"Americans have a fundamental right to know how their food is being produced, but right now, the only way to gather this information is to break the law.\" Responding to an inquiry from ''The Times'', Smithfield leveled accusations that the group has a history of manipulating footage in order to \"mislead the public and gain attention for its activist agenda which includes 'total animal liberation.'\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Andrew |first=Jacobs |date=August 4, 2019 |title=Stealing Lauri|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/04/science/stealing-lauri.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location= |access-date=August 6, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Philosophy==\n\n=== \"Humane fraud\" ===\nDxE has had an ongoing campaign against companies who make claims about selling food products made with \"humane\" standards of animal welfare. Targets of this campaign have included the supermarket [[Whole Foods Market]], the restaurant chain [[Chipotle Mexican Grill]], and several farms. Through its investigations, public statements and writings, protests, and livestock theft, DxE has alleged that such companies misrepresent the actual conditions on their farms or their suppliers' farms. DxE also maintains that it is not possible to raise and kill animals in a humane way.<ref name=\"WaPo\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2014/03/02/dont_buy_the_chipotle_hype_theres_no_such_thing_as_humane_slaughter/|title=Don't buy the Chipotle hype: There's no such thing as \"humane\" slaughter|last=Gazzola|first=Lauren|website=Salon|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Social science ===\nDxE\u2019s leaders include a number of students of social science, and DxE organizers aim to use social science in persuading others to join their protests and self-proclaimed rescues. DxE has published articles on the evidence for nonviolent civil resistance based on the work of political scientist Erica Chenoweth, the importance of social ties based on the work of sociologist Doug McAdam, and the importance of mobilizing masses of ordinary people based on research by network scientist Duncan Watts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/direct-action-everywhere-dxe/four-reasons-why-direct-action-leads-to-animal-liberation-edf64953d7f5|title=Four Reasons Why Direct Action Leads to Animal Liberation \u2013 Direct Action Everywhere (DxE)|last=Groff|first=Zach|date=2016-10-19|website=Medium|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/direct-action-everywhere-dxe/a-potential-summary-of-disagreements-and-agreements-on-direct-action-18fb8703f409|title=A (Potential) Summary of Disagreements and Agreements on Direct Action \u2013 Direct Action Everywhere (DxE)|last=Groff|first=Zach|date=2016-10-21|website=Medium|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical stance toward consumer veganism ===\nActivists and writers associated with DxE have criticized the animal rights movement\u2019s contemporary focus on creating individual vegans and celebrating consumer products like vegan ice cream rather than focusing on activism and changing social and political institutions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://veganpublishers.com/wayne-hsiung-the-evolution-of-veganism-is-empowered-activism-the-next-stage/|title=Vegan Publishers|website=veganpublishers.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012123923/http://veganpublishers.com/wayne-hsiung-the-evolution-of-veganism-is-empowered-activism-the-next-stage/|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> DxE argues that the individual focus is less effective than trying to change institutions, since the individual focus does not lead people to do more once they stop using animals personally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://veganfeministagitator.blogspot.com/2014/10/ten-questions-vegan-rockstar-edition_29.html|title=The Vegan Street Blog from the Vegan Feminist Agitator: Ten Questions: Vegan Rockstar Edition with Wayne Hsiung|last=Marla|date=2014-10-29|website=The Vegan Street Blog from the Vegan Feminist Agitator|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref> Instead, DxE argues that activist groups should push people to take action so that the movement grows more quickly.<ref name=\":1\" /> Activists with DxE have argued that nonviolence is in principle a practice of anger toward systems and compassion toward individuals and that a protest movement will be more successful by focusing on governments, corporations, and other institutions rather than making individual consumers defensive by attacking them personally.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2015/10/21/stigmatizing-eating-animals|title=Stigmatizing Eating Animals|newspaper=Direct Action Everywhere|access-date=2017-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDxE\u2019s blog has argued that consumer vegan options also distract from the actual threat to animals, allowing companies that are hurting animals like Whole Foods to avoid criticism and leading animal rights activists not to take action against them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2015/3/5/dear-animal-advocates-vegan-options-are-not-animal-liberation|title=Vegan Options are Not Animal Liberation|newspaper=Direct Action Everywhere|access-date=2017-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref> In a debate with Rutgers philosopher and animal rights theorist [[Gary L. Francione|Gary Francione]], DxE co-founder Wayne Hsiung stated that \u201cactivism, not veganism, is the moral baseline.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.goveganradio.com/26-july-2015/|title=Go Vegan Radio {{!}} Archives {{!}} 26 July 2015|last=Admin|website=www.goveganradio.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Tactics ==\n\n=== Open rescue ===\nWayne Hsiung cites as an inspiration for DxE the work of Patty Mark, an Australian animal rights activist and founder of [[Animal Liberation Victoria|Animal Liberation Victoria (ALV)]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2014/11/24/on-the-shoulders-of-giants|title=On the Shoulders of Giants|newspaper=Direct Action Everywhere|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-US}}</ref> ALV activists popularized the tactic of going into farms in the middle of the night without disguises and filming the conditions inside.<ref>[http://www.rescate-abierto.org/que-es-rescate-abierto.php Rescate abierto de animales] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304000812/http://rescate-abierto.org/que-es-rescate-abierto.php |date=2009-03-04 }} [[Equanimal]] (in spanish)</ref> The tactic stands in contrast to the more common form of investigation in the U.S. animal rights movement in which an investigator poses as a farm worker to film using a hidden camera. Open rescue activists {{Who|date=April 2017}} emphasize that their approach allows the portrayal of individual animals\u2019 stories since activists can focus on animals in the farm, and to rescue animals who would otherwise die of disease  document their recovery.<ref>Ronnie Rose, \u201cThe Power of Open Rescue\u201d, ''Satya Magazine.'' 2016 Self-published version can be found here: https://medium.com/@ronnierose/the-power-of-open-rescue-58b250323a32</ref> It {{Who|date=April 2017}} also touts open rescue as a form of activism anyone can undertake, offering the possibility and goal of thousands of open rescue teams across the country.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nDxE has cited open rescues as particularly key to exposing \u201chumane\u201d companies that are generally smaller and more difficult to infiltrate.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2015/1/9/on-the-importance-of-open-rescue-three-reasons-the-ar-movement-has-to-get-serious-about-liberation|title=On the Importance of Open Rescue: Four Reasons to Get Serious about Liberation|newspaper=Direct Action Everywhere|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-US}}</ref>  In April 2016, three members of DxE went undercover to Yulin, China, home of the Yulin dog meat festival, to document the upcoming preparations of the festival; they said they\u2019ve been able to catch some of the brutality on camera at one of the largest slaughterhouses in the city.<ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/celebrities-square-off-chinese-dog-meat-festival/story?id=40031828|title=Celebrities Square Off Against Chinese Dog Meat Festival|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref>  Two of the activists with DxE were able to smuggle out the video footage they had captured, along with three dogs bound for slaughter.<ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Berkeley-City-Council-passed-a-resolution-against-9237403.php|title=Berkeley City Council passed a resolution against eating dogs last night|last=Spotswood|first=Beth|date=2016-09-21|website=SFGate|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref>\n\nOpen rescue has been criticized by one such smaller, \"humane\" company that has been the target of DxE's use of the tactic. Petaluma Farms, a distributor of eggs for Whole Foods, was investigated and the subject of a highly publicized campaign and open rescue of DxE's. Jonathan Mahrt, an employee of Petaluma Farms and son of Petaluma Farms' owner Steven Mahrt, said, \"My dad\u2019s take is that it\u2019s a sad day when farmers and ranchers have to be concerned about security.\" <ref name=\"Petaluma Argus-Courier\" />\n\nOn May 29, 2018 several hundred DxE demonstrators held a protest outside Cal Eggs Farm in Petaluma, CA, and 40 of the activists entered a barn and carried out live and diseased birds. These 40 activists were arrested for misdemeanor trespassing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.petaluma360.com/news/8377254-181/animal-rights-activists-hold-large|title=Dozens of animal welfare activists arrested after large protest at Petaluma chicken farm|date=2018-05-29|work=Petaluma Argus Courier|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> DxE activists believe that they have the legal right to rescue animals from farms in California described in state laws, and they want to establish this right in courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/Animal-Rights-Activists-Protest-Chicken-Facility-in-Sonoma-County-494717591.html|title=Animal Rights Activists Arrested at Chicken Facility Protest|last=News|first=Bay City|website=NBC Bay Area|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Amanda says\"/>\n\nA major open rescue action was held on Saturday, September 29, 2018 at Petaluma Farms, the supplier to Amazon and Whole Foods, and the largest in the US. Several dying hens were removed from filthy, crowded sheds. One hen was allowed to leave with the activists and was sent to a sanctuary, however the rest were sent to animal control and did not survive. Petaluma sheriff's office reported that 67 activists were arrested at the scene. DxE counted it was 58 activists who were arrested. After release, activists continue to protest against police unlawfulness, despite the activists having the right to the open rescue under California penal law code statue 597E, Doctrine of Necessity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?lawCode=PEN&sectionNum=597e|title=Law section|website=leginfo.legislature.ca.gov|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref> The activists are continuing to fight to be allowed to continue open rescues.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2018/09/29/67-animal-rights-activists-arrested-trying-to-remove-chickens-from-petaluma-farm/|title=67 Animal Rights Activists Arrested Trying To Remove Chickens From Petaluma Farm|date=2018-09-29|access-date=2018-11-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Mass protests ===\nInspired by both activist networks and street theater groups such as [[Improv Everywhere]], DxE mobilizes masses of activists to creative protest in prominent public spaces. Early actions in DxE\u2019s history include a guerilla poem, a \u201cfreeze\u201d at a prominent mall, the disruption of a screening of American Meat with the stories and images of companion animals, and numerous other creative efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stanforddaily.com/2013/02/13/op-ed-a-response-to-the-american-meat-protest-from-dxe/|title=Op-Ed: A Response to the American Meat Protest From DxE|last=Ed|first=Op|website=Stanford Daily|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n\nNotable network-wide protests have included an effort in the summer of 2015 to incorporate dogs, cats, and other companion animals into protests as a symbol of human support, connections, and equality with animals. DxE also issued the #DisruptSpeciesism and #DogMeatPlease viral video challenges in September 2014 and 2015, respectively, which garnered social media fame when videos by DxE organizers Priya Sawhney, Kelly Atlas, and Jenny McQueen went viral.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/animal-rights-activists-stormed-a-toronto-steakhouse-to-protest-societys-meat-eating-habits|title=Animal Rights Activists Stormed a Toronto Steakhouse to Protest Society's Meat Lust - VICE|website=Vice|language=en-us|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hlntv.com/video/2014/10/13/its-not-food-its-violence-vegan-rant-snow-chicken|title=Vegan rant goes viral: 'This isn't food, it's violence' {{!}} HLNtv.com|last=staff|first=Dr. Drew|newspaper=HLNtv.com|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, DxE co-hosted a rally with Compassionate Bay in support of Supervisor Katy Tang of San Francisco leading the effort to ban the sale of fur in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebaycitybeacon.com/politics/supervisor-s-fur-ban-pits-high-fashion-against-modern-animal/article_b7f87ec2-0623-11e8-a1b9-57f64f48f5fa.html|title=Supervisor's Fur Ban Pits High Fashion Against Modern Animal Ethics|last=Writer|first=Mike Ege; Senior Staff|website=thebaycitybeacon.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> Later that month, the board of supervisors of San Francisco voted unanimously to ban the sale of new fur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2018/03/20/san-francisco-fur-sales-ban/444519002/|title=San Francisco becomes largest U.S. city to ban fur sales|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Disruption of public events ===\nActivists within the DxE network have undertaken a number of prominent disruptions of public figures. In August 2015, Iowa activist Matt Johnson asked New Jersey Governor [[Chris Christie]] about his veto of a widely supported bill banning gestation crates for mother pigs that the public widely regarded as cruel.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/22/politics/chris-christie-iowa-state-fair-hecklers-pork/index.html|title=Christie ribbed by animal rights activists at Iowa State Fair|author=Betsy Klein and Maggie Loughran|website=CNN|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n\nJohnson staged similar disruptions along the campaign trail, including at Iowa campaign events by Ohio Governor [[John Kasich]] and former U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] and an appearance by former Hewlett Packard CEO [[Carly Fiorina]] at the Iowa Pork Producers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/iowa-poll/2015/09/26/kasich-talks-tough-cyber-security-iowa-forum/72826844/|title=Kasich talks tough on cybersecurity at Iowa forum|newspaper=Des Moines Register|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/258013-animal-rights-protestor-interrupts-bill-clinton|title=Animal-rights protestor interrupts Bill Clinton|last=Smilowitz|first=Elliot|date=2015-10-24|newspaper=TheHill|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thinkprogress.org/politics/2016/01/27/3743643/fiorina-interrupted-pork-farmers-event/|title=Faced With Animal Rights Activist, Fiorina Defends Pork Farmers By Attacking Abortion|last=Atkin|first=Emily|date=2016-01-28|newspaper=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref> Fiorina replied to Johnson\u2019s protest by condemning him for protesting for animals and not the lives of unborn children. Several activists from Iowa and Indiana also interrupted a Republican family values forum on the eve of Thanksgiving and the release of DxE\u2019s Diestel Turkey Ranch investigation video.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3328023/Immigration-protesters-crash-Christian-GOP-candidate-forum-Iowa-don-t-care-law.html|title=Immigration protesters crash Christian candidate forum in Iowa|newspaper=Mail Online|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, activists interrupted a speech by Pennsylvania Governor [[Tom Wolf (politician)|Tom Wolf]] at the 100th anniversary of the [[Pennsylvania Farm Show]], saying that there was no reason to confine and kill pigs, chickens, and cows when it was not okay to do that to dogs or cats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/01/animal_rights_activists_farm_s.html|title=Animal activists escorted out of 2016 Farm Show|newspaper=PennLive.com|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-US}}</ref> DxE activist Zach Groff has stated that DxE aims to ensure that any event or public figure \u201cpromoting violence against animals\u201d is the target of a protest interruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.porknetwork.com/community/thompson-stuff-animal-rights-activists-say|title=Thompson: Stuff animal rights activists say {{!}} Pork Network|website=www.porknetwork.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222053418/http://www.porknetwork.com/community/thompson-stuff-animal-rights-activists-say|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2015/4/17/how-a-former-lonely-vegan-ended-up-confronting-the-secretary-of-agriculture|title=How a Former Lonely Vegan Ended up Confronting the Secretary of Agriculture|newspaper=Direct Action Everywhere|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nDirect Action Everywhere has received criticism from vegan and non-vegan consumers, and the shops and farms they have targeted. [[Benny Johnson (journalist)|Benny Johnson]] of the [[Independent Journal Review]] has called their protest tactics in Berkeley \"bullying\" in regards to graphic Berkeley protests in the summer of 2017.<ref name=\"IJROPED\">{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Benny|title=Mom and Pop Butcher Shop Bullied by Vegans Until They Agreed to Post This Sign in Their Store|url=http://ijr.com/2017/08/939006-mom-pop-butcher-shop-bullied-vegans-agreed-post-sign-store|website=IJR - Independent Journal Review|publisher=Independent Journal Review|accessdate=25 February 2018|ref=IJROPED|date=3 August 2017}}</ref> [[Alice Waters]], proprietor of the [[Chez Panisse]], was a target of some of these protests and called them an \"outrage\" and that the DxE protestors \"need to do their homework\".<ref name=\"NBCBUTCHER\">{{cite web|last1=Quintana|first1=Sergio|title=Berkeley Butcher Shop Makes a Deal With Animal Rights Group|url=https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/Berkeley-Butcher-Shop-Makes-a-Deal-With-Animal-Rights-Group-438370453.html|website=NBC Bay Area|publisher=National Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=25 February 2018|ref=NBCBUTCHER|language=en}}</ref> On the subject of these protests and the protesters' knowledge of humane food, the Director of Operations for [[Certified Humane]], Mimi Stein, said in an email to the [[Washington Post]] that \u201cDxE is attempting to undermine consumer confidence in products which are in fact ethically produced and businesses working in good faith to reinvigorate a very desirable traditional business model...Shame on DxE!\u201d<ref name=\"WAPOBUTCHER\">{{cite web|last1=Judkis|first1=Maura|title=Bowing to pressure, a Berkeley butcher shop makes a deal with vegan protesters|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/food/wp/2017/08/02/vegan-protesters-get-butcher-shop-to-say-killing-animals-is-wrong-but-not-to-stop-doing-it/|website=Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=25 February 2018|ref=WAPOBUTCHER|date=2 August 2017}}</ref> Lauren-Elizabeth McGrath of vegan magazine Ecorazzi commented in 2016 that \"They\u2019re an organization that is set on disrupting the day of the average meat-eater, but fails to help them beyond just that\" and discussed accusations of racism within the organisation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ecorazzi.com/2016/01/22/slow-burn-the-internal-implosion-of-direct-action-everywhere/|title=Slow burn: The internal implosion of Direct Action Everywhere|\nlast=McGrath|first=Lauren-Elizabeth|date= 22 January 2016|work=Ecorazzi}}</ref> [[Carol J. Adams|Carol Adams]], vegetarian-feminist and author of [[The Sexual Politics of Meat]], announced on her blog that she intends to boycott events that host DxE speakers, stating that \"DxE is both a counterproductive organization [for activism] as well as cult.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caroljadams.com/carol-adams-blog/why-i-am-boycotting-events-if-dxe-is-also-an-invited-speaker|title=Carol J Adams}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Hsiung and four others were charged in Utah with felonies for burglary, livestock theft, and engaging in a pattern of illegal activity and misdeameanor for engaging in a riot. They were identified after posting high-quality video online of taking pigs from a Smithfield Foods facility in [[Beaver County, Utah]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900019252/5-animal-rights-activists-charged-with-pilfering-pigs-in-utah.html|title=5 animal rights activists charged with pilfering pigs in Utah|last=Reavy|first=Pat|work=Deseret News|date=21 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"wired-5dec2019\">{{cite magazine |last=Greenberg | first=Andy |authorlink1=Andy Greenberg | title=Meet the Activists Risking Prison to Film VR in Factory Farms |url=https://www.wired.com/story/direct-action-everywhere-virtual-reality-exposing-factory-farms/ |accessdate=December 5, 2019 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|WIRED]] |date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{external media\n| align  = right\n| width  = 220px\n| video1 = {{YouTube|5PSTrcc386w|They Rescued Pigs and Turkeys From Factory Farms \u2014 and Now Face Decades in Prison}}}}\n\n*[http://directactioneverywhere.com/ Direct Action Everywhere official site]\n\n{{Animal rights|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Animal rights organizations]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Berkeley, California]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2013]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{COI|date=July 2019}}\n{{Advert|date=July 2019}}\n{{Globalize|article|USA|date=January 2020}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox organization\n|name         = Direct Action Everywhere\n|logo         = Dxe logo.svg\n|logo_size    = 100\n|image        = Direct Action Everywhere protest at Whole Foods Market.jpg\n|caption      = DxE protest at a [[Whole Foods Market]] in San Francisco, July 2015\n|map          =\n|msize        = \n|mcaption     = \n|abbreviation = DxE\n|motto        = \n|formation    = 2013\n|type         = \n|status       = \n|purpose      = [[Animal rights]]\n|headquarters = [[Berkeley, California]]\n|location     = \n|region_served = \n|membership   = \n|language     =\n|leader_title = \n|leader_name  = \n|main_organ   = \n|parent_organization = \n|affiliations = \n|num_staff    = \n|num_volunteers =\n|budget       = \n|website      = {{plainlink|http://directactioneverywhere.com|directactioneverywhere.com}}\n|remarks      =\n}}\n\n'''Direct Action Everywhere''' ('''DxE''') is an international [[grassroots]] network of [[animal rights]] activists founded in 2013 in the San Francisco Bay Area.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/handbook|title=Direct Action Everywhere handbook|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref> DxE activists started with disruptive protests but now also use non-violent [[direct action]] tactics to further their cause, such as [[open rescue]] of animals from factory farms.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thenewjournalatyale.com/2015/03/everyday-evil/|title=Everyday Evil|last=Boodman|first=Eric|date=March 20, 2015|publisher=The New Journal|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref> Their intent is to build a movement that can eventually shift culture and change social and political institutions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailykos.com/story/2016/06/01/1532982/-Fighting-Speciesism-with-Direct-Action-Animal-Rights-Activists-DxE-Disrupt-Sanders-Oakland-Rally|title=Fighting Speciesism with Direct Action: Animal Rights Activists DxE Disrupt Sanders' Oakland Rally|last=Wilkins|first=Brett|date=May 31, 2016|publisher=Daily Kos|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref> DxE activists work to \"put an end to the commodity status of animals.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=https://munchies.vice.com/en/articles/why-these-vegans-are-protesting-bernie-sanders-rallies|title=Why These Vegans Are Protesting Bernie Sanders Rallies|last=Woods|first=Nick|date=March 31, 2016|publisher=Vice|accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===Founding===\nDxE was founded in 2013 by a handful of people in the San Francisco Bay Area who decided to protest inside restaurants and stores, rather than outside, which was more typical of animal rights protests.<ref name=\"whyinside\">{{cite web |url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2014/4/8/why-dxe-brings-the-message-inside | title=Why DxE Brings the Message Inside | accessdate=August 23, 2016}}</ref> DxE co-founder [[Wayne Hsiung]] investigated slaughterhouses for ten years prior to founding DxE with the goal of scaling up [[open rescue]] and other forms of non-violent direct action.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animalcharityevaluators.org/resources/conversations-and-interviews/conversation-with-wayne-hsiung-direct-action-everywhere/|title=Conversation with Wayne Hsiung, Direct Action Everywhere|accessdate=August 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDxE's first action occurred in January 2013.<ref name=firstvid>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=w5wffvHafRY&x-yt-ts=1421914688&x-yt-cl=84503534 |website=YouTube |title=It Starts With You...|date=January 8, 2013|accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref> Six activists demonstrated in front of a meat counter at a [[Sprouts Farmers Market]], contending that the items being sold there behind the counter were not food but \"the torment and suffering of billions of our friends in factory farms and slaughterhouses.\"<ref name=\"firstvid\" />\n\n===Growth===\nDxE continued organizing protests inside restaurants and stores, citing the [[Southern Christian Leadership Conference]] and [[ACT UP]] as influences.<ref name=ourhenhouse>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourhenhouse.org/WayneHsiungEpisode245.pdf |website=[[Our Hen House]] |title=Interview with Wayne Hsiung | date=September 20, 2014 | accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref> In August 2013, DxE   activists organized the Los Angeles side of an international multi-city protest, The Earthlings March.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailynews.com/social-affairs/20130824/animal-rights-activists-march-in-downtown-la|title=Animal Rights Activists March in Downtown LA | last=Goff|first=Kelly|date=August 24, 2013|publisher=Los Angeles Daily News|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref> Approximately 40 cities and varied activist groups participated in the march.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.jpost.com/Enviro-Tech/Animal-activists-take-over-Tel-Avivs-Rothschild-Boulevard-324132|title=Animal Activists Take Over Tel Aviv's Rothschild Boulevard | last=Goff|first=Kelly|date=August 24, 2013|publisher=Los Angeles Daily News|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, in response to a viral video produced by [[Chipotle]] called The Scarecrow, DxE organized in-store \u201cdie-ins\u201d at three San Francisco Chipotle restaurants.<ref name=scarecrow>{{cite web|url=tps://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lUtnas5ScSE |website=YouTube |title=The Scarecrow|date=September 11, 2013|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"newfrontier\">{{cite web |url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2013/10/21/the-new-frontier | title=The New Frontier | accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref> DxE argued that the ad, which advertised Chipotle\u2019s purported efforts to create a more natural and humane food system was \u201chumanewashing,\u201d which animal rights activists describe as marketing efforts intended to disguise the inherent violence of using and killing animals for food.<ref name=\"chipotlestart\">{{cite web |url=http://static1.squarespace.com/static/515cca87e4b0bca14d767b61/t/526304cfe4b0971963e4897d/1382221007692/2013.10.19+Killing+is+no+Kindness+Press+Release.pdf | title=Activists in Six Cities \"Die-In\" at Chipotle | accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref> Within a few weeks, similar demonstrations were executed in Chicago, Los Angeles, Phoenix and Philadelphia. DxE responded by creating a platform for coordinated global days of action under the \u201cIt\u2019s Not Food, It\u2019s Violence\u201d message.<ref name=\"chipotlestart\" />\n\nDxE has continued with internationally coordinated monthly days of action. In addition to Chipotle, activists have also targeted other grocery stores, restaurants, clothing stores, zoos, circuses, and labs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2015/05/24/18772659.php | title=Animal Rights Protest in San Francisco | last=Boyer|first=D.|date=May 24, 2014|publisher=Indybay|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.greenisthenewred.com/blog/utah-protest-prosecution/8521/ | title=BREAKING: 2 Animal Activists Facing 6 Months in Jail for Protesting on the Sidewalk | last=Potter|first=Will|date=August 20, 2015|publisher=Green Is The New Red|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nbclosangeles.com/news/local/Clowns-Brawl-With-Protesters-Under-Circus-Big-Top-San-Bernardino-300490891.html | title=Clowns Brawl With Protesters Under Circus Big Top in San Bernardino | last=Larkin|first=Michael|date=April 17, 2015|publisher=NBC Los Angeles|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://yaledailynews.com/blog/2015/03/23/animal-rights-activists-protest-use-of-animals-in-yale-labs/ | title=Animal rights activists protest use of animals in Yale labs | last=Chua|first=Jun Yua|date=March 23, 2015|publisher=Yale Daily News|accessdate=September 5, 2016}}</ref> The original actions were organized around the San Francisco Bay Area. By December 2014, DxE's network had grown to at least 90 cities in 20 countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D4dkK3tI7X8 |website=YouTube | title=Stop the Violence - DxE December Day of Action | date=January 20, 2015 | accessdate=January 25, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDxE hosts an annual Animal Liberation Conference (ALC) for grassroots, peaceful animal rights activists.<ref name=\"plantbasednews.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.plantbasednews.org/post/arrested-held-1-million-bond-vegan-activist|title='We Were Arrested And Held On $1 Million Bond' - A Vegan Activist Speaks Out|website=www.plantbasednews.org|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> The ALC is a full week of talks, trainings, and socials all aimed at empowering activists.<ref name=\"plantbasednews.org\"/>\n\n===Whole Foods campaign===\nDxE selected U.S.-based natural foods grocery store [[Whole Foods Market]] as the target of the investigation because the company is allegedly \u201cactively shaping the public\u2019s view of animal agriculture with false marketing.\u201d<ref name=\"Why Whole Foods\">{{cite web|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2014/12/2/why-whole-foods | title=Why Target Whole Foods?|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe activists selected Certified Humane Whole Foods egg supplier Petaluma Farms in Petaluma, California, as the target of the initial investigation.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/01/09/business/direct-action-everywhere-video-of-laying-hens-raises-concerns.html|title=Animal Rights Group's Video of Hens Raises Questions, but Not Just for Farms|date=January 8, 2015|work=New York Times|accessdate=2015-01-12}}</ref> At one point, activists encountered a diseased hen who had collapsed and was struggling to breathe and removed her from the farm. They named her Mei Hua (Chinese for \u201cbeautiful flower\u201d) and made her recovery a centerpiece of the ensuing campaign and imagery.<ref name=\"Mei Hua\">{{cite web|url=http://freefromharm.org/animal-cruelty-investigation/one-survivors-story-whole-foods-humane-hoax/ | title=One Survivor's Story|date=January 15, 2015|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Petaluma Argus-Courier\">{{cite web|url=http://www.petaluma360.com/news/3374941-181/activists-targeting-petalumafarmers|title=Activists Targeting Petaluma Farmers|last=Charrier|first=Emily|date=2015-01-15|accessdate=2017-04-24}}</ref> Another farm owned by the same company was later the subject of a similar video filmed by a former employee. When asked for comment about that particular break-in after DxE's release of their initial video, the [[Sonoma County]] Sheriff's Department stated that a full investigation was underway, but that the farm appeared to be performing at \"industry standards.\"<ref name=\"Petaluma Argus-Courier\" />\n\nDxE released a 19-minute video of the investigation, \u201cTruth Matters,\u201d on YouTube and Facebook in January 2015 and received coverage in several international media outlets, including The New York Times and Mother Jones.<ref name=\"NYT\" /><ref name=\"MJ\">{{cite news|url=https://www.motherjones.com/tom-philpott/2015/01/you-cant-produce-eggs-industrial-scale-without-breaking-few-hens|title=What Does \"Cage Free\" Even Mean?|date=January 14, 2015|publisher=Mother Jones|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref> For several weekends following the investigation, and every month thereafter through early 2016, DxE chapters in several dozen cities organized protests inside Whole Foods stores, challenging the company\u2019s \u201cValues Matter\u201d advertising campaign.<ref name=\"Philly\">{{cite news|url=http://www.philly.com/philly/blogs/pets/Group-to-hold-Philly-protest-against-cruel-conditions-at-humane-egg-farm-.html\n|title=Group to protest Whole Foods over egg farm conditions|date=January 10, 2015|publisher=philly.com|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"NHR\">{{cite news|url=http://www.nhregister.com/article/NH/20150112/NEWS/150119864|title=Animal rights activists demonstrate at Whole Foods in Milford over egg supplier|date=January 12, 2015|publisher=New Haven Register|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref> Whole Foods announced new egg-laying standards shortly after the release of the investigation video.<ref name=\"NYT\" />\n\nOver the course of 2015, a larger team of activists investigated Diestel Turkey Ranch, one of only three companies, out of over 2,000, to achieve a 5+ rating on the 1\u20135 scale used by the Global Animal Partnership, Whole Foods\u2019s animal welfare rating scheme.<ref name=\"WaPo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/morning-mix/wp/2015/11/24/whole-foods-thanksgiving-turkeys-endure-horrific-conditions-at-calif-farm-animal-rights-activists-say/|title=Whole Foods Thanksgiving turkeys endure 'horrific conditions' at Calif. farm, activists say|date=November 24, 2015|publisher=Washington Post|accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"WSJ\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/video-shows-abuse-at-whole-foods-turkey-supplier-activists-say-1448328713|title=Video Shows Abuse at Whole Foods Turkey Supplier, Activists Say|date=November 23, 2015|publisher=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=September 20, 2015}}</ref> Activists recorded video reportedly at a Diestel-owned farm in Jamestown, CA, showing filth, overcrowding, and birds dying as infants.<ref name=\"Diestel\">{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=byb8WjknZxw |website=YouTube | title=Where does Whole Foods turkey really come from? | date=November 23, 2015 | accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref> Diestel added a brief mention to its website of its Jamestown farm following the investigation.<ref name=\"Diestel Website\">{{cite web|url=http://www.diestelturkey.com | title=Diestel Turkey |accessdate=September 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\nDxE released another investigation in November 2016 into Jaindl Farms, a Whole Foods farm that has supplied the White House with Thanksgiving turkeys since the 1960s rated in the 98th percentile of animal welfare according to an animal welfare audit.<ref name=\"Jaindl WaPo\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/animalia/wp/2016/11/18/turkeys-supplied-to-white-house-are-raised-in-inhumane-conditions-activist-group-says/|title= Turkeys supplied to White House are raised in inhumane conditions, activist group says|date=November 18, 2016|publisher=Washington Post|accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Jaindl Website\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jaindl.com/about/ | title=Jaindl |accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref> The activists released footage of birds with mutilated beaks, struggling to walk, and crowded to the point of repeated trampling.<ref name=\"Jaindl WaPo\" /> The video footage from the farm that DxE released shows birds with mangled beaks, broken legs, missing eyes, open sores and facial lesions.<ref name=\"Jaindl HuffPo\"/> In one scene, turkeys peck and nibble at a young bird\u2019s festering wound.<ref name=\"Jaindl HuffPo\"/> In another, a decaying carcass rests on the floor among live animals.<ref name=\"Jaindl HuffPo\"/> Two Huffington Post reporters visited the farm on invitation of Jaindl's owner and found that while severe injuries were uncommon, turkeys had visible sores.<ref name=\"Jaindl HuffPo\">{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/jaindl-turkeys-white-house_us_582dbea7e4b030997bbda895|title=  The Turkey Farm That Supplies The White House Says It's Humane. See For Yourself.|date=November 22, 2016|publisher=Huffington Post|accessdate=November 30, 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn May 29, 2018 several hundred DxE activists held a protest outside Cal Eggs Farm in Petaluma, CA, which is a supplier to Whole Foods. Some of the activists entered a barn and carried out live and diseased birds. 40 of the activists were arrested for misdemeanor trespassing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2018/05/29/animal-rights-activists-stage-huge-protest-at-petaluma-egg-farm/|title=Animal Rights Activists Stage Huge Protest At Petaluma Egg Farm|date=2018-05-29|access-date=2018-11-12|language=en}}</ref> DxE activists see \"open rescue\" as establishing \"the right to rescue\" animals legally in the future.<ref name=\"Amanda says\">{{Cite web|url=https://sanfrancisco.cbslocal.com/2018/09/21/whole-foods-takes-legal-action-against-berkeley-animal-rights-group/|title=Whole Foods Takes Legal Action Against Berkeley Animal Rights Group|last=Amanda says|date=2018-09-21|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref>\n\nAfter numerous protests inside the Whole Foods store in Berkeley, CA, Whole Foods obtained a restraining order against DxE activists in September 2018, prohibiting Wayne Hsiung and 150 other unnamed DxE activists from entering that particular store or its parking lot.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2018/oct/05/whole-foods-animal-rights-protest-restraining-order|title=Whole Foods v vegans: Berkeley store gets restraining order against activists|last=Canon|first=Gabrielle|date=2018-10-05|website=the Guardian|language=en|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref>\n\n=== Liberation Pledge ===\nIn November 2015, DxE became one of the most visible backers of a new action known as the \"Liberation Pledge,\" with co-founder Wayne Hsiung authoring a piece in the ''Huffington Post'' announcing the pledge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/wayne-hsiung/post_10470_b_8480886.html|title=How Animal Lovers Are Transforming Thanksgiving|last=Hsiung|first=Wayne|date=2015-11-06|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=|access-date=2016-12-19}}</ref> According to the website liberationpledge.com, it is defined by the following three points:\n\n{{quote|One: Publicly refuse to eat animals\u2014live vegan.{{br}}\nTwo: Publicly refuse to sit where people are eating animals.{{br}}\nThree: Encourage others to take the pledge.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liberationpledge.com|title=The Liberation Pledge|website=www.liberationpledge.com|access-date=2016-12-19}}</ref>}}\n\nThe pledge was considered controversial upon release, including criticisms regarding [[food justice]] concerns and by potentially isolating vegans who take the pledge.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thecommentist.com/beardedvegans14/|title=Should vegans take the Liberation Pledge? \u2013 Episode 14|last=The Bearded Vegans|date=2015-11-21|newspaper=The Commentist|language=English|access-date=2016-12-19|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170218113347/http://thecommentist.com/beardedvegans14/|archive-date=2017-02-18|url-status=dead}}</ref> Several prominent figures in the animal rights movement, including [[Anita Krajnc case|Anita Krajnc]] of the Toronto Pig Save and [[Keith McHenry]] of [[Food Not Bombs]] took the pledge, with McHenry declaring, \"We must stop the eating of animals.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.liberationpledge.com/our-words|title=Our Words \u2014 The Liberation Pledge|website=www.liberationpledge.com|access-date=2016-12-19}}</ref> Wanyama Box creator Nzinga Young defended the Liberation Pledge, writing, \"when I spend time in safe spaces with sacred people, I don\u2019t want to see carnage.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/nzinga-young/i-dont-let-my-friends-eat_b_11575264.html|title=I Don't Let Friends Eat Meat In My Presence|last=Young|first=Nzinga|date=2016-08-20|website=The Huffington Post|publisher=|access-date=2016-12-19}}</ref>\n\n===Costco campaign===\nFollowing the Farmer John investigation, DxE activists repeatedly interrupted [[LA Dodgers]] baseball games to protest the team's touting of Farmer John's \"Dodger Dogs\" hot dogs.<ref name=\"Angel Pagan EBT\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.eastbaytimes.com/2016/10/01/angel-pagan-slam-why-the-protester-ran-on-field/|title=Angel Pagan slam: Protester speaks out on why he ran on field|last=Gafni|first=Matthias|date=2016-10-01|website=East Bay Times|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"LA Dodgers PE\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pe.com/articles/group-807391-treatment-ingredients.html|title=DODGERS: Animal rights activists removed after running onto field during protest over hot dogs|date=2016-07-03|website=Press Enterprise|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref> Activists in LA, Colorado, and the San Francisco Bay Area jumped on the field during plays at several games with banners declaring \"Dodgers Torture Animals\" and \"Animal Liberation Now.\"<ref name=\"Angel Pagan EBT\" /><ref name=\"LA Dodgers PE\" /><ref name=\"LA Dodgers AP\">{{Cite web|url=http://gazette.com/protesters-jump-over-wall-rush-the-field-during-rockies-dodgers-game/article/1581825|title=Protesters jump over wall, rush the field during Rockies-Dodgers game|agency=Associated Press|date=2016-08-03|website=Colorado Gazette|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref> The activists tied their protests to Farmer John, protesting the promotion of \"torture and death of animals.\"<ref name=\"Angel Pagan EBT\" />\n\nDxE followed up its Farmer John investigation by investigating a cage-free egg supplier to Costco.<ref name=\"Costco NYT\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/21/business/video-reveals-how-cage-free-hens-live-animal-advocates-say.html?_r=0|title=How 'Cage-Free' Hens Live, in Animal Advocates' Video|last=Strom|first=Stephanie|date=2016-10-20|website=The New York Times|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref> Costco had been a key leader in the 2016 trend of food companies committing to shift to a cage-free egg supply, but, according to DxE, the investigation raised questions about the state of animal welfare after that shift.<ref name=\"Costco Quartz\">{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/582427/after-months-of-pressure-costco-commits-to-a-cage-free-egg-supply/|title=After months of pressure, Costco commits to a cage-free egg supply|last=Shanker|first=Deena|date=2015-12-28|website=Quartz|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref><ref name=\"Costco NYT\" />  DxE released a video that shows dead birds on the floor and injured hens pecked by other chickens. One bird had a piece of flesh hanging off its beak.<ref name=\"Strom\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/21/business/video-reveals-how-cage-free-hens-live-animal-advocates-say.html|title=How 'Cage-Free' Hens Live, in Animal Advocates' Video|last=Strom|first=Stephanie|date=2016-10-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-03-04|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In response to the video released by DxE, the supplier claimed that the activists had committed a \"break-in and trespassing\" and that \"The video does not show what truly goes on in our barns and appears to be staged for production effect\".<ref name=\"Costco NYT\" /> The group did not seek permission to enter the farm, Lead Organizer Wayne Hsiung said, but he argued that the group had not broken any laws because they had suspected animal cruelty and that gave them a right to enter the property.<ref name=\"Strom\"/> All birds inside the farm were destroyed due to the contamination risk the activists had introduced into the farm, according to the supplier.<ref name=\"Costco NYT\" /> The two DxE organizers who conducted the investigation were initially charged with felony commercial burglary and subsequently pleaded no-contest to a reduced charge of trespass.<ref name=\"indybay.org\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indybay.org/newsitems/2019/02/19/18821286.php|title=Costco Egg Supplier Seeks to Bankrupt Animal Investigators|website=Indybay|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> The defendants were then ordered to pay restitution of $331,991 to compensate the farm owner based on his assertion that he was forced to slaughter all chickens in the barn. The defendants claim that the \"depopulated\" chickens were in a barn they never entered.<ref name=\"indybay.org\"/>\n\nDirect Action Everywhere staged a protest at the SoMa location of Costco in San Francisco. Direct Action Everywhere activists forcibly occupied the store's meat section and held a \"die-in\" near an entrance that involved activists covering each other with fake blood and pretending to eat each other. Another protest was held at a Costco store in New Berlin, Wisconsin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Armed-with-fake-blood-animal-rights-activists-10154372.php|title=Armed with fake blood, animal-rights activists protest at SF Costco|last=Johnson|first=Lizzie|date=2016-10-23|website=SF Gate|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wisconsingazette.com/2016/12/21/animal-rights-activists-protest-inside-new-berlin-costco/|title=Animal rights activists protest inside New Berlin Costco|last=Swartz|first=Tim|date=2016-12-21|website=Wisconsin Gazette|access-date=2017-01-30}}</ref>\n\n=== Open rescue expansion ===\nIn December 2016, DxE open rescue projects began expanding beyond the Bay Area when members in Toronto released an investigation of a pig farm.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedodo.com/baby-pig-factory-farm-2151716622.html|title=They Saw This Baby Pig And Knew They Had To Save Her Life|date=2016-12-16|work=The Dodo - For Animal People|access-date=2017-04-17|language=en}}</ref> The project was followed up by an internationally coordinated rescue with animal advocates in Sweden, Germany, and Australia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dailycal.org/2017/03/07/animals-rescued-unsafe-farm-conditions/|title=Animals should be rescued from unsafe farm conditions|last=Cal|first=Cassie King {{!}} Special to the Daily|date=2017-03-07|website=The Daily Californian|access-date=2017-04-17}}</ref> In April 2017, DxE activists in Colorado conducted an investigation of Morning Fresh Farms, a cage-free chicken egg supplier.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/NowThisPolitics/|title=NowThis Politics|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2017-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, activists with DxE entered [[Smithfield Foods]]-owned Circle Four Farms in Utah and performed an Open Rescue of two piglets subsequently named Lily and Lizzie. Their rescue triggered an extensive multi-state FBI hunt for the two baby piglets.<ref>{{cite news |last= Greenwald|first=Glenn|date=October 5, 2017 |title=The FBI's Hunt for Two Missing Piglets Reveals the Federal Cover-Up of Barbaric Factory Farms|url=https://theintercept.com/2017/10/05/factory-farms-fbi-missing-piglets-animal-rights-glenn-greenwald/|work=[[The Intercept]]|authorlink=Glenn Greenwald|access-date=October 5, 2017}}</ref>  DxE released a virtual-reality video that takes viewers into barns at Circle Four Farms and shows sows with bloody and mangled teats; pregnant sows gnawing on the bars of the narrow stalls they live in until they give birth; and piglets clambering over and nibbling dead siblings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/07/06/dining/animal-welfare-virtual-reality-video-meat-industry.html|title=Animal Welfare Groups Have a New Tool: Virtual Reality|last=Strom|first=Stephanie|date=2017-07-06|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-02-11|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> A video taken by DxE that coincided with the Open Rescue at Circle Four Farms has been called inaccurate by a spokesman for Smithfield; the video purports to show mistreatment and abuse of animals at Circle Four Farms.<ref name=\"DCSmithfield\">{{cite web|last1=Bear|first1=John|title=Animal rights organization says FBI search at Erie sanctuary related to 'rescue' of piglets from Utah|url=http://www.dailycamera.com/erie-news/ci_31305664/animal-rights-organization-says-fbi-search-at-erie|website=Boulder Daily Camera|publisher=Digital First Media|accessdate=23 November 2017}}</ref> In November the same year, a group of DxE activists, which included actress [[Alexandra Paul]], claimed to expose animal cruelty and neglect at Zonneveld Dairy, a [[Land O'Lakes]] dairy supplier based in California, which included \"young calves living in filthy hutches, unprotected from record low and high temperatures between 19 and 110 degrees Fahrenheit, suffering from pneumonia, diarrhea, open sores, maggot infestations, and infections.\" The team of activists performed an Open Rescue on one sick calf, later named Roselynn.<ref>{{cite news |last=Butler|first=Kiera|date=November 7, 2017|title=Inside the Bold New Animal Liberation Movement: No Masks, No Regrets, All the Risk|url=https://www.motherjones.com/food/2017/11/inside-the-bold-new-animal-liberation-movement-no-masks-no-regrets-all-the-risk/|work=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]|location= |access-date=November 9, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Starostinetskaya |first=Anna|date=November 8, 2017 |title=Rampant Animal Cruelty Exposed at Land O'Lakes|url=http://vegnews.com/articles/page.do?pageId=10348&catId=1|work=[[VegNews]]|location= |access-date=November 9, 2017 }}</ref>\n\nIn September, 2017 DxE organizers attended a small-scale poultry processing class at Long Shadow Farm, a 6-acre farm in Berthoud, Colorado specializing in pasture-raised chickens. The facility raises animals and offers \"poultry processing services.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.reporterherald.com/news/larimer-county/ci_31310944/denver-animal-rights-group-says-it-rescued-chickens|title=Denver animal rights group says it 'rescued' chickens from Berthoud family farm|website=www.reporterherald.com|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> Led by DxE Organizer Aidan Cook, under the name of \"Denver Baby Animal Save\" the group entered the property masquerading as volunteers<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.reporterherald.com/news/larimer-county/ci_31310944/denver-animal-rights-group-says-it-rescued-chickens|title=Denver animal rights group says it 'rescued' chickens from Berthoud family farm|access-date=2017-10-18}}</ref> and took three chickens, after asking to hold some of the birds and being assisted in doing so by the farm owners' 8 year old daughter. Opinions on the actions vary, with DxE organizers and members claiming to have \"rescued\" the birds, while the farm owners considered it \"theft\". A DxE spokesperson stated that \"even if the animal rights group could have saved more chickens by purchasing them, the group opposes buying into a system that hurts animals.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> The DxE organizers who conducted the \"open rescue\" responded to an inquiry by the farm owner, \"We have taken your birds to a sanctuary, where they can be free.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/09/19/animal-rights-group-steals-chickens-farm/680951001/|title=Animal rights group steals chickens from farm to 'free' them|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> Two of the chickens that were taken were carriers of [[Mycoplasma gallisepticum|mycoplasma]], a highly infectious respiratory disease in poultry.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/09/19/animal-rights-group-steals-chickens-farm/680951001/|title=Animal rights group steals chickens from farm to 'free' them|work=USA TODAY|access-date=2017-10-18|language=en}}</ref> The Larimer County Sheriff's Office is investigating several felony allegations including trespassing, attempted theft of livestock and theft of livestock.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.coloradoan.com/story/news/2017/09/18/denver-based-animal-rights-group-steals-chickens-berthoud-farm/678055001/|title=Denver-based animal rights group steals chickens from Berthoud farm|work=Coloradoan|access-date=2017-10-18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, a Utah prosecutor filed felony charges against six DxE activists stemming from an undercover investigation into conditions on a turkey farm in Moroni, Utah which serves as a supplier for [[Norbest]]. The DxE investigation found \"tens of thousands of turkeys crammed inside filthy industrial barns, virtually on top of one another.\"{{Citation needed|reason=Where is this quote from??|date=September 2019}}  The activists rescued three turkeys suffering from disease or injuries and were on the brink of death. The charges include two felony theft charges that carry possible prison terms of five years each.<ref>{{cite news |last=Greenwald |first=Glenn |date=May 4, 2018 |title=Six Animal Rights Activists Charged With Felonies for Investigation and Rescue That Led to Punishment of a Utah Turkey Farm |url=https://theintercept.com/2018/05/04/six-animal-rights-activists-charged-with-felonies-for-investigation-and-rescue-that-led-to-punishment-of-a-utah-turkey-farm/|work= The Intercept|location= |access-date=May 4, 2018 }}</ref> In October 2018 the verdict of the judge was to allow 3 of the defendants to perform community service in lieu of further punishment if they plead guilty to misdemeanors. However, Wayne Hsiung and Paul Darwin Picklesimer will have to go through an additional trial to determine the final verdict.\n\nIn April 2019, DxE activists broke into a Smithfield Foods farm in North Carolina to expose overcrowding and unsanitary conditions there, and the extensive use of antibiotics. In addition to acquiring footage of scores of sick piglets and refrigerators full of powerful antibiotics, the group took a 6 week old female pig, subsequently named Lauri, and rushed her to a vet. Testing revealed Lauri suffered from pneumonia, anemia and an antibiotic-resistant staph infection. She now resides at an animal sanctuary. Hsiung, who was involved in the raid on the farm, told ''The New York Times'' \"Americans have a fundamental right to know how their food is being produced, but right now, the only way to gather this information is to break the law.\" Responding to an inquiry from ''The Times'', Smithfield leveled accusations that the group has a history of manipulating footage in order to \"mislead the public and gain attention for its activist agenda which includes 'total animal liberation.'\"<ref>{{cite news |last=Andrew |first=Jacobs |date=August 4, 2019 |title=Stealing Lauri|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/08/04/science/stealing-lauri.html |work=[[The New York Times]] |location= |access-date=August 6, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Philosophy==\n\n=== \"Humane fraud\" ===\nDxE has had an ongoing campaign against companies who make claims about selling food products made with \"humane\" standards of animal welfare. Targets of this campaign have included the supermarket [[Whole Foods Market]], the restaurant chain [[Chipotle Mexican Grill]], and several farms. Through its investigations, public statements and writings, protests, and livestock theft, DxE has alleged that such companies misrepresent the actual conditions on their farms or their suppliers' farms. DxE also maintains that it is not possible to raise and kill animals in a humane way.<ref name=\"WaPo\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.salon.com/2014/03/02/dont_buy_the_chipotle_hype_theres_no_such_thing_as_humane_slaughter/|title=Don't buy the Chipotle hype: There's no such thing as \"humane\" slaughter|last=Gazzola|first=Lauren|website=Salon|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref>\n\n=== Social science ===\nDxE\u2019s leaders include a number of students of social science, and DxE organizers aim to use social science in persuading others to join their protests and self-proclaimed rescues. DxE has published articles on the evidence for nonviolent civil resistance based on the work of political scientist Erica Chenoweth, the importance of social ties based on the work of sociologist Doug McAdam, and the importance of mobilizing masses of ordinary people based on research by network scientist Duncan Watts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/direct-action-everywhere-dxe/four-reasons-why-direct-action-leads-to-animal-liberation-edf64953d7f5|title=Four Reasons Why Direct Action Leads to Animal Liberation \u2013 Direct Action Everywhere (DxE)|last=Groff|first=Zach|date=2016-10-19|website=Medium|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/direct-action-everywhere-dxe/a-potential-summary-of-disagreements-and-agreements-on-direct-action-18fb8703f409|title=A (Potential) Summary of Disagreements and Agreements on Direct Action \u2013 Direct Action Everywhere (DxE)|last=Groff|first=Zach|date=2016-10-21|website=Medium|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n\n=== Critical stance toward consumer veganism ===\nActivists and writers associated with DxE have criticized the animal rights movement\u2019s contemporary focus on creating individual vegans and celebrating consumer products like vegan ice cream rather than focusing on activism and changing social and political institutions.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://veganpublishers.com/wayne-hsiung-the-evolution-of-veganism-is-empowered-activism-the-next-stage/|title=Vegan Publishers|website=veganpublishers.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171012123923/http://veganpublishers.com/wayne-hsiung-the-evolution-of-veganism-is-empowered-activism-the-next-stage/|archive-date=2017-10-12|url-status=dead}}</ref> DxE argues that the individual focus is less effective than trying to change institutions, since the individual focus does not lead people to do more once they stop using animals personally.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://veganfeministagitator.blogspot.com/2014/10/ten-questions-vegan-rockstar-edition_29.html|title=The Vegan Street Blog from the Vegan Feminist Agitator: Ten Questions: Vegan Rockstar Edition with Wayne Hsiung|last=Marla|date=2014-10-29|website=The Vegan Street Blog from the Vegan Feminist Agitator|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref> Instead, DxE argues that activist groups should push people to take action so that the movement grows more quickly.<ref name=\":1\" /> Activists with DxE have argued that nonviolence is in principle a practice of anger toward systems and compassion toward individuals and that a protest movement will be more successful by focusing on governments, corporations, and other institutions rather than making individual consumers defensive by attacking them personally.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2015/10/21/stigmatizing-eating-animals|title=Stigmatizing Eating Animals|newspaper=Direct Action Everywhere|access-date=2017-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nDxE\u2019s blog has argued that consumer vegan options also distract from the actual threat to animals, allowing companies that are hurting animals like Whole Foods to avoid criticism and leading animal rights activists not to take action against them.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2015/3/5/dear-animal-advocates-vegan-options-are-not-animal-liberation|title=Vegan Options are Not Animal Liberation|newspaper=Direct Action Everywhere|access-date=2017-02-13|language=en-US}}</ref> In a debate with Rutgers philosopher and animal rights theorist [[Gary L. Francione|Gary Francione]], DxE co-founder Wayne Hsiung stated that \u201cactivism, not veganism, is the moral baseline.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.goveganradio.com/26-july-2015/|title=Go Vegan Radio {{!}} Archives {{!}} 26 July 2015|last=Admin|website=www.goveganradio.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-02-13}}</ref>\n\n== Tactics ==\n\n=== Open rescue ===\nWayne Hsiung cites as an inspiration for DxE the work of Patty Mark, an Australian animal rights activist and founder of [[Animal Liberation Victoria|Animal Liberation Victoria (ALV)]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2014/11/24/on-the-shoulders-of-giants|title=On the Shoulders of Giants|newspaper=Direct Action Everywhere|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-US}}</ref> ALV activists popularized the tactic of going into farms in the middle of the night without disguises and filming the conditions inside.<ref>[http://www.rescate-abierto.org/que-es-rescate-abierto.php Rescate abierto de animales] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304000812/http://rescate-abierto.org/que-es-rescate-abierto.php |date=2009-03-04 }} [[Equanimal]] (in spanish)</ref> The tactic stands in contrast to the more common form of investigation in the U.S. animal rights movement in which an investigator poses as a farm worker to film using a hidden camera. Open rescue activists {{Who|date=April 2017}} emphasize that their approach allows the portrayal of individual animals\u2019 stories since activists can focus on animals in the farm, and to rescue animals who would otherwise die of disease  document their recovery.<ref>Ronnie Rose, \u201cThe Power of Open Rescue\u201d, ''Satya Magazine.'' 2016 Self-published version can be found here: https://medium.com/@ronnierose/the-power-of-open-rescue-58b250323a32</ref> It {{Who|date=April 2017}} also touts open rescue as a form of activism anyone can undertake, offering the possibility and goal of thousands of open rescue teams across the country.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nDxE has cited open rescues as particularly key to exposing \u201chumane\u201d companies that are generally smaller and more difficult to infiltrate.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2015/1/9/on-the-importance-of-open-rescue-three-reasons-the-ar-movement-has-to-get-serious-about-liberation|title=On the Importance of Open Rescue: Four Reasons to Get Serious about Liberation|newspaper=Direct Action Everywhere|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-US}}</ref>  In April 2016, three members of DxE went undercover to Yulin, China, home of the Yulin dog meat festival, to document the upcoming preparations of the festival; they said they\u2019ve been able to catch some of the brutality on camera at one of the largest slaughterhouses in the city.<ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/International/celebrities-square-off-chinese-dog-meat-festival/story?id=40031828|title=Celebrities Square Off Against Chinese Dog Meat Festival|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref>  Two of the activists with DxE were able to smuggle out the video footage they had captured, along with three dogs bound for slaughter.<ref name=\"abcnews.go.com\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sfgate.com/bayarea/article/Berkeley-City-Council-passed-a-resolution-against-9237403.php|title=Berkeley City Council passed a resolution against eating dogs last night|last=Spotswood|first=Beth|date=2016-09-21|website=SFGate|access-date=2019-02-11}}</ref>\n\nOpen rescue has been criticized by one such smaller, \"humane\" company that has been the target of DxE's use of the tactic. Petaluma Farms, a distributor of eggs for Whole Foods, was investigated and the subject of a highly publicized campaign and open rescue of DxE's. Jonathan Mahrt, an employee of Petaluma Farms and son of Petaluma Farms' owner Steven Mahrt, said, \"My dad\u2019s take is that it\u2019s a sad day when farmers and ranchers have to be concerned about security.\" <ref name=\"Petaluma Argus-Courier\" />\n\nOn May 29, 2018 several hundred DxE demonstrators held a protest outside Cal Eggs Farm in Petaluma, CA, and 40 of the activists entered a barn and carried out live and diseased birds. These 40 activists were arrested for misdemeanor trespassing.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.petaluma360.com/news/8377254-181/animal-rights-activists-hold-large|title=Dozens of animal welfare activists arrested after large protest at Petaluma chicken farm|date=2018-05-29|work=Petaluma Argus Courier|access-date=2018-11-12}}</ref> DxE activists believe that they have the legal right to rescue animals from farms in California described in state laws, and they want to establish this right in courts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/Animal-Rights-Activists-Protest-Chicken-Facility-in-Sonoma-County-494717591.html|title=Animal Rights Activists Arrested at Chicken Facility Protest|last=News|first=Bay City|website=NBC Bay Area|language=en|access-date=2019-02-18}}</ref><ref name=\"Amanda says\"/>\n\nA major open rescue action was held on Saturday, September 29, 2018 at Petaluma Farms, the supplier to Amazon and Whole Foods, and the largest in the US. Several dying hens were removed from filthy, crowded sheds. One hen was allowed to leave with the activists and was sent to a sanctuary, however the rest were sent to animal control and did not survive. Petaluma sheriff's office reported that 67 activists were arrested at the scene. DxE counted it was 58 activists who were arrested. After release, activists continue to protest against police unlawfulness, despite the activists having the right to the open rescue under California penal law code statue 597E, Doctrine of Necessity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leginfo.legislature.ca.gov/faces/codes_displaySection.xhtml?lawCode=PEN&sectionNum=597e|title=Law section|website=leginfo.legislature.ca.gov|accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref> The activists are continuing to fight to be allowed to continue open rescues.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sacramento.cbslocal.com/2018/09/29/67-animal-rights-activists-arrested-trying-to-remove-chickens-from-petaluma-farm/|title=67 Animal Rights Activists Arrested Trying To Remove Chickens From Petaluma Farm|date=2018-09-29|access-date=2018-11-12|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Mass protests ===\nInspired by both activist networks and street theater groups such as [[Improv Everywhere]], DxE mobilizes masses of activists to creative protest in prominent public spaces. Early actions in DxE\u2019s history include a guerilla poem, a \u201cfreeze\u201d at a prominent mall, the disruption of a screening of American Meat with the stories and images of companion animals, and numerous other creative efforts.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stanforddaily.com/2013/02/13/op-ed-a-response-to-the-american-meat-protest-from-dxe/|title=Op-Ed: A Response to the American Meat Protest From DxE|last=Ed|first=Op|website=Stanford Daily|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n\nNotable network-wide protests have included an effort in the summer of 2015 to incorporate dogs, cats, and other companion animals into protests as a symbol of human support, connections, and equality with animals. DxE also issued the #DisruptSpeciesism and #DogMeatPlease viral video challenges in September 2014 and 2015, respectively, which garnered social media fame when videos by DxE organizers Priya Sawhney, Kelly Atlas, and Jenny McQueen went viral.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vice.com/read/animal-rights-activists-stormed-a-toronto-steakhouse-to-protest-societys-meat-eating-habits|title=Animal Rights Activists Stormed a Toronto Steakhouse to Protest Society's Meat Lust - VICE|website=Vice|language=en-us|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.hlntv.com/video/2014/10/13/its-not-food-its-violence-vegan-rant-snow-chicken|title=Vegan rant goes viral: 'This isn't food, it's violence' {{!}} HLNtv.com|last=staff|first=Dr. Drew|newspaper=HLNtv.com|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, DxE co-hosted a rally with Compassionate Bay in support of Supervisor Katy Tang of San Francisco leading the effort to ban the sale of fur in the city.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thebaycitybeacon.com/politics/supervisor-s-fur-ban-pits-high-fashion-against-modern-animal/article_b7f87ec2-0623-11e8-a1b9-57f64f48f5fa.html|title=Supervisor's Fur Ban Pits High Fashion Against Modern Animal Ethics|last=Writer|first=Mike Ege; Senior Staff|website=thebaycitybeacon.com|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref> Later that month, the board of supervisors of San Francisco voted unanimously to ban the sale of new fur.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2018/03/20/san-francisco-fur-sales-ban/444519002/|title=San Francisco becomes largest U.S. city to ban fur sales|website=USA TODAY|language=en|access-date=2019-02-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Disruption of public events ===\nActivists within the DxE network have undertaken a number of prominent disruptions of public figures. In August 2015, Iowa activist Matt Johnson asked New Jersey Governor [[Chris Christie]] about his veto of a widely supported bill banning gestation crates for mother pigs that the public widely regarded as cruel.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2015/08/22/politics/chris-christie-iowa-state-fair-hecklers-pork/index.html|title=Christie ribbed by animal rights activists at Iowa State Fair|author=Betsy Klein and Maggie Loughran|website=CNN|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n\nJohnson staged similar disruptions along the campaign trail, including at Iowa campaign events by Ohio Governor [[John Kasich]] and former U.S. President [[Bill Clinton]] and an appearance by former Hewlett Packard CEO [[Carly Fiorina]] at the Iowa Pork Producers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.desmoinesregister.com/story/news/politics/iowa-poll/2015/09/26/kasich-talks-tough-cyber-security-iowa-forum/72826844/|title=Kasich talks tough on cybersecurity at Iowa forum|newspaper=Des Moines Register|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/258013-animal-rights-protestor-interrupts-bill-clinton|title=Animal-rights protestor interrupts Bill Clinton|last=Smilowitz|first=Elliot|date=2015-10-24|newspaper=TheHill|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thinkprogress.org/politics/2016/01/27/3743643/fiorina-interrupted-pork-farmers-event/|title=Faced With Animal Rights Activist, Fiorina Defends Pork Farmers By Attacking Abortion|last=Atkin|first=Emily|date=2016-01-28|newspaper=ThinkProgress|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref> Fiorina replied to Johnson\u2019s protest by condemning him for protesting for animals and not the lives of unborn children. Several activists from Iowa and Indiana also interrupted a Republican family values forum on the eve of Thanksgiving and the release of DxE\u2019s Diestel Turkey Ranch investigation video.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3328023/Immigration-protesters-crash-Christian-GOP-candidate-forum-Iowa-don-t-care-law.html|title=Immigration protesters crash Christian candidate forum in Iowa|newspaper=Mail Online|access-date=2017-02-21}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, activists interrupted a speech by Pennsylvania Governor [[Tom Wolf (politician)|Tom Wolf]] at the 100th anniversary of the [[Pennsylvania Farm Show]], saying that there was no reason to confine and kill pigs, chickens, and cows when it was not okay to do that to dogs or cats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/01/animal_rights_activists_farm_s.html|title=Animal activists escorted out of 2016 Farm Show|newspaper=PennLive.com|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-US}}</ref> DxE activist Zach Groff has stated that DxE aims to ensure that any event or public figure \u201cpromoting violence against animals\u201d is the target of a protest interruption.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.porknetwork.com/community/thompson-stuff-animal-rights-activists-say|title=Thompson: Stuff animal rights activists say {{!}} Pork Network|website=www.porknetwork.com|language=en|access-date=2017-02-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222053418/http://www.porknetwork.com/community/thompson-stuff-animal-rights-activists-say|archive-date=2017-02-22|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://directactioneverywhere.com/theliberationist/2015/4/17/how-a-former-lonely-vegan-ended-up-confronting-the-secretary-of-agriculture|title=How a Former Lonely Vegan Ended up Confronting the Secretary of Agriculture|newspaper=Direct Action Everywhere|access-date=2017-02-21|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\nDirect Action Everywhere has received criticism from vegan and non-vegan consumers, and the shops and farms they have targeted. [[Benny Johnson (journalist)|Benny Johnson]] of the [[Independent Journal Review]] has called their protest tactics in Berkeley \"bullying\" in regards to graphic Berkeley protests in the summer of 2017.<ref name=\"IJROPED\">{{cite web|last1=Johnson|first1=Benny|title=Mom and Pop Butcher Shop Bullied by Vegans Until They Agreed to Post This Sign in Their Store|url=http://ijr.com/2017/08/939006-mom-pop-butcher-shop-bullied-vegans-agreed-post-sign-store|website=IJR - Independent Journal Review|publisher=Independent Journal Review|accessdate=25 February 2018|ref=IJROPED|date=3 August 2017}}</ref> [[Alice Waters]], proprietor of the [[Chez Panisse]], was a target of some of these protests and called them an \"outrage\" and that the DxE protestors \"need to do their homework\".<ref name=\"NBCBUTCHER\">{{cite web|last1=Quintana|first1=Sergio|title=Berkeley Butcher Shop Makes a Deal With Animal Rights Group|url=https://www.nbcbayarea.com/news/local/Berkeley-Butcher-Shop-Makes-a-Deal-With-Animal-Rights-Group-438370453.html|website=NBC Bay Area|publisher=National Broadcasting Corporation|accessdate=25 February 2018|ref=NBCBUTCHER|language=en}}</ref> On the subject of these protests and the protesters' knowledge of humane food, the Director of Operations for [[Certified Humane]], Mimi Stein, said in an email to the [[Washington Post]] that \u201cDxE is attempting to undermine consumer confidence in products which are in fact ethically produced and businesses working in good faith to reinvigorate a very desirable traditional business model...Shame on DxE!\u201d<ref name=\"WAPOBUTCHER\">{{cite web|last1=Judkis|first1=Maura|title=Bowing to pressure, a Berkeley butcher shop makes a deal with vegan protesters|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/food/wp/2017/08/02/vegan-protesters-get-butcher-shop-to-say-killing-animals-is-wrong-but-not-to-stop-doing-it/|website=Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=25 February 2018|ref=WAPOBUTCHER|date=2 August 2017}}</ref> Lauren-Elizabeth McGrath of vegan magazine Ecorazzi commented in 2016 that \"They\u2019re an organization that is set on disrupting the day of the average meat-eater, but fails to help them beyond just that\" and discussed accusations of racism within the organisation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ecorazzi.com/2016/01/22/slow-burn-the-internal-implosion-of-direct-action-everywhere/|title=Slow burn: The internal implosion of Direct Action Everywhere|\nlast=McGrath|first=Lauren-Elizabeth|date= 22 January 2016|work=Ecorazzi}}</ref> [[Carol J. Adams|Carol Adams]], vegetarian-feminist and author of [[The Sexual Politics of Meat]], announced on her blog that she intends to boycott events that host DxE speakers, stating that \"DxE is both a counterproductive organization [for activism] as well as cult.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://caroljadams.com/carol-adams-blog/why-i-am-boycotting-events-if-dxe-is-also-an-invited-speaker|title=Carol J Adams}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Hsiung and four others were charged in Utah with felonies for burglary, livestock theft, and engaging in a pattern of illegal activity and misdeameanor for engaging in a riot. They were identified after posting high-quality video online of taking pigs from a Smithfield Foods facility in [[Beaver County, Utah]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.deseretnews.com/article/900019252/5-animal-rights-activists-charged-with-pilfering-pigs-in-utah.html|title=5 animal rights activists charged with pilfering pigs in Utah|last=Reavy|first=Pat|work=Deseret News|date=21 May 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"wired-5dec2019\">{{cite magazine |last=Greenberg | first=Andy |authorlink1=Andy Greenberg | title=Meet the Activists Risking Prison to Film VR in Factory Farms |url=https://www.wired.com/story/direct-action-everywhere-virtual-reality-exposing-factory-farms/ |accessdate=December 5, 2019 |work=[[Wired (magazine)|WIRED]] |date=December 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{external media\n| align  = right\n| width  = 220px\n| video1 = {{YouTube|5PSTrcc386w|They Rescued Pigs and Turkeys From Factory Farms \u2014 and Now Face Decades in Prison}}}}\n\n*[http://directactioneverywhere.com/ Direct Action Everywhere official site]\n\n{{Animal rights|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Animal rights organizations]]\n[[Category:Animal welfare organizations based in the United States]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Berkeley, California]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2013]]\n", "name_user": "95.150.167.115", "label": "unsafe", "comment": 