{"title_page": "Basher Dimalaang Manalao", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Aleem\n| name               = Basher D. Manalao\n| image              = Mostaqbal.jpg\n| caption            = Photo of Aleem Mostaqbal\n| nationality        = Filipino\n| organization       = Philippine Al-Mostaqbal, Inc.\n| known_for          = Missioner\n| home_town          = Tamparan, Lanao del Sur, Philippines\n}}\n\n'''Basher Dimalaang Manalao''' or known to be '''Mostaqbal''', a [[Maranao people]], Islamic preacher (''[[Ulama]]'' or ''[[Aleem]]'') and was elected vice-governor then succeeded by law the governor of [[Lanao del Sur]] in the [[Philippines]] following the death of former governor [[Mamintal Alonto Adiong Jr.|Mamintal Adiong Sr]]. in 2004. He took his Islamic degree (''Arabic'': \u0643\u0648\u0644\u064a\u062a) at [[King Saud University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2004/07/12/257243/manalao-takes-over-lanao-sur-governor|title=Manalao takes over as Lanao Sur governor|last=De La Cruz|first=Lino|date=July 12, 2004|work=The Philippine Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe owns an organization Philippine Al-Mostaqbal Incorporation educating members about Islamic cultures, future, and [[Quran|science of Qur\u2019an]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dateliners.net/2019/05/27/bta-religious-rep-perceive-peace-in-the-night-of-decree/|title=BTA religious rep: Perceive peace in The Night of Decree|last=Saaduddin|first=Deh|date=May 27, 2019|work=Dateliners News|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/289134|title=SU Graduate Brings Lanao Del Sur\u2019s Leadership Closer to People|last=Tago|first=Abdul Hanan|date=September 19, 2006|work=Arab News|access-date=}}</ref> Dominant members of his organization were women. The organization established a Facebook page named \u201cMostaqbal Online Channel\u201d with having over 8.5k followers. He had little or no interest in politics.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe established a public cemetery called \u201cMaqbara\u201d located at Barangay Guimba, [[Marawi|Marawi City]], [[Lanao del Sur]] in the [[Philippines]] during his term as governor of the province.<ref name=\":0\" /> Due to political dispute, he was suspended in 3 months by a petition of Monera Macabangon in 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2006/04/20/332297/lanao-sur-exec-stopped-withdrawing-funds|title=Lanao Sur exec stopped from withdrawing funds|last=De La Cruz|first=Lino|date=April 20, 2006|work=The Philippine Star|access-date=}}</ref> He then returned to the office of governor by the decision of the court.\n\n== Early life ==\nMostaqbal was born in his home town [[Tamparan, Lanao del Sur]] in the Philippines. He graduated high school at [[Jamiatu Muslim Mindanao|Ma\u2019ahad Mindanao Al-Arabi]] newly [[Jamiatu Muslim Mindanao]] and proceeded to Islamic education at [[King Saud University]].\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]]\n*[[Bangsamoro Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]]\n*[[Jamiatu Muslim Mindanao]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />{{Lanao del Sur}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Filipino Muslims]]\n[[Category:King Saud University alumni]]\n[[Category:Filipino missionaries]]\n[[Category:People from Lanao del Sur]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = Aleem\n| name               = Basher D. Manalao\n| image              = Mostaqbal.jpg\n| caption            = Photo of Aleem Mostaqbal\n| nationality        = Filipino\n| organization       = Philippine Al-Mostaqbal, Inc.\n| known_for          = Missioner\n| home_town          = Tamparan, Lanao del Sur, Philippines\n}}\n\n'''Basher Dimalaang Manalao''' or known to be '''Mostaqbal''', a [[Maranao people]], Islamic preacher (''[[Ulama]]'' or ''[[Aleem]]'') and was elected vice-governor then succeeded by law the governor of [[Lanao del Sur]] in the [[Philippines]] following the death of former governor [[Mamintal Alonto Adiong Jr.|Mamintal Adiong Sr]]. in 2004. He took his Islamic degree (''Arabic'': \u0643\u0648\u0644\u064a\u062a) at [[King Saud University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2004/07/12/257243/manalao-takes-over-lanao-sur-governor|title=Manalao takes over as Lanao Sur governor|last=De La Cruz|first=Lino|date=July 12, 2004|work=The Philippine Star|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nHe owns an organization Philippine Al-Mostaqbal Incorporation educating members about Islamic cultures, future, and [[Quran|science of Qur\u2019an]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dateliners.net/2019/05/27/bta-religious-rep-perceive-peace-in-the-night-of-decree/|title=BTA religious rep: Perceive peace in The Night of Decree|last=Saaduddin|first=Deh|date=May 27, 2019|work=Dateliners News|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.arabnews.com/node/289134|title=SU Graduate Brings Lanao Del Sur\u2019s Leadership Closer to People|last=Tago|first=Abdul Hanan|date=September 19, 2006|work=Arab News|access-date=}}</ref> Dominant members of his organization were women. The organization established a Facebook page named \u201cMostaqbal Online Channel\u201d with having over 8.5k followers. He had little or no interest in politics.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nHe established a public cemetery called \u201cMaqbara\u201d located at Barangay Guimba, [[Marawi|Marawi City]], [[Lanao del Sur]] in the [[Philippines]] during his term as governor of the province.<ref name=\":0\" /> Due to political dispute, he was suspended in 3 months by a petition of Monera Macabangon in 2006.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2006/04/20/332297/lanao-sur-exec-stopped-withdrawing-funds|title=Lanao Sur exec stopped from withdrawing funds|last=De La Cruz|first=Lino|date=April 20, 2006|work=The Philippine Star|access-date=}}</ref> He then returned to the office of governor by the decision of the court.\n\n== Early life ==\nMostaqbal was born in his home town [[Tamparan, Lanao del Sur]] in the Philippines. He graduated high school at [[Jamiatu Muslim Mindanao|Ma\u2019ahad Mindanao Al-Arabi]] newly [[Jamiatu Muslim Mindanao]] and proceeded to Islamic education at [[King Saud University]].\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]]\n*[[Bangsamoro Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao]]\n*[[Jamiatu Muslim Mindanao]]\n\n== References ==\n<references />{{Lanao del Sur}}\n\n[[Category:Filipino Muslims]]\n[[Category:King Saud University alumni]]\n[[Category:Filipino missionaries]]\n[[Category:People from Lanao del Sur]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basher_Dimalaang_Manalao"}
{"title_page": "Rosa Kato", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2011}}\n{{Update|date=July 2016}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Rosa Kato\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Rosa Kato\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1985|06|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Kagoshima]], Japan\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| other_names = Rosa Matsui (married)\n| occupation = [[Actress]], [[model (person)|model]]\n| yearsactive = 2001&ndash;present\n| spouse = [[Daisuke Matsui]] (22 June 2011&ndash;present)\n| children = 2\n| domesticpartner =\n| website = {{URL|www.ken-on.co.jp/rosa/}}\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Rosa Kato'''|\u52a0\u85e4 \u30ed\u30fc\u30b5|Kat\u014d R\u014dsa|born 22 June 1985}} is a Japanese [[actress]] and [[commercial model]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Career===\nFrom April 2004 to March 2005, Kato was a regular guest student on ''Italian Conversation'',<ref>[http://www.nhk.or.jp/gogaku/italian/tv/index.html NHK Italian TV Conversation]</ref> a 25-minute [[NHK]] TV program for beginners of Italian. She subsequently began appearing in commercials and became a popular model after appearing in ''Zexy'', a Japanese [[bridal]] magazine, in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-postseven.com/archives/20110703_24906.html|title=NEWS\u30dd\u30b9\u30c8\u30bb\u30d6\u30f3\uff5c\u52a0\u85e4\u30ed\u30fc\u30b5\u306e\u610f\u5916\u3068\u300c\u30ae\u30e3\u30eb\u300d\u306a\u7d20\u9854\u306b\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30af\u53d7\u3051\u308b\u4eba\u591a\u6570|publisher=News-postseven.com|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared in the Japanese film ''Tokyo Tower'' with [[Jun Matsumoto]] in 2005. In late 2005, she began appearing in [[Japanese television dramas]] such as ''Kindaichi Shonen no Jikenbo''. She later won the \"Best Newcomer Award\" for her performance in ''Dance Drill'' (also known as ''Dandori'' in Japan) in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvdrama-db.com/drama_info/p/id-39242 |title=\u30c0\u30f3\u30c9\u30ea\u3002 - \u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u8a73\u7d30\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf - \u25c7\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9\u25c7|publisher=Tvdrama-db.com|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, she starred in the Japanese drama ''Jotei'' with [[Hana Yori Dango]] actor [[Shota Matsuda]]. In 2008, Kato appeared in several TV dramas such as ''Oh! My Girl!'' with [[Mokomichi Hayami]] and ''Change'' with [[Takuya Kimura]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n===Early life===\nKato's mother is [[Japanese people|Japanese]] and her father is [[Italians|Italian]], both met at an Italian restaurant her father worked at in [[Yokohama]]. When Kato was five years old, the family moved to [[Naples]], Italy. At that time she was able to speak and understand Italian, but has since forgotten almost every word. Hence, Kato was a regular guest student on Italian Conversation [[NHK]] TV program.<ref>[http://www.nhk.or.jp/gogaku/italian/tv/index.html NHK Italian TV Conversation], nhk.or.jp; accessed 20 June 2016.</ref> She was named Rosa after her paternal grandmother.<ref>[http://www.nipponcinema.com/tag/rosa-kato Rosa Kato in Nippon Cinema], nipponcinema.com; accessed 20 June 2016. {{in lang|en}}</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nOn 22 June 2011, Kato's 26th birthday, she married Japanese football player [[Daisuke Matsui]].<ref>[http://www.houseofjapan.com/movies/matsui-marries-actress-kato \"Matsui marries actress Kato\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317114420/http://www.houseofjapan.com/movies/matsui-marries-actress-kato |date=2012-03-17 }}, houseofjapan.com; 23 June 2011; retrieved 3 July 2011.</ref> The next day, she announced on her blog her four-month pregnancy with their first child.<ref>[http://www.tokyohive.com/2011/06/kato-rosa-marries-soccer-player-matsui-daisuke-4-months-pregnant Kato Rosa marries soccer player Matsui Daisuke & is 4 months pregnant!] 22 June 2011; retrieved 3 July 2011.</ref> She later gave birth to a son.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://www.ken-on.co.jp/2011/12/post_181.html|title=\u52a0\u85e4\u30ed\u30fc\u30b5\u3088\u308a\u30d5\u30a1\u30f3\u306e\u7686\u3055\u307e\u3078|publisher=KEN-ON|date=14 December 2011|accessdate=5 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120613012212/http://www.ken-on.co.jp/2011/12/post_181.html|archivedate=13 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2005\n|''[[Tokyo Tower (film)|Tokyo Tower]]''\n|-\n|''Simsons''\n|-\n|''A Day Beyond The Horizon: Itsuka Nami no Kanata ni''\n|-\n|rowspan=5|2006\n|''Catch A Wave''\n|-\n|''Youki na Gang ga Chikyuu wo Mawasu''\n|-\n|''Ichiban Kirei na Mizu''\n|-\n|''Yoru no Pikunikku (Night Time Picnic)''\n|-\n|''Taki 183''\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2007\n|''Unfair: The Movie''\n|-\n|''Smile Seiya no Kiseki''\n|-\n|''Pok\u00e9mon 10th Movie: Dialga Vs. Palkia Vs. Darkrai''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2008\n|''[[Detroit Metal City#Film|Detroit Metal City]]''\n|-\n|''Tengoku wa Mada Tooku''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2012\n|''Girls For Keeps (Garu)''\n|}\n\n=== TV dramas ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Network\n|-\n| ''Division 1 - Yuku Na Ryoma!'' || 2005 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| ''Kindaichi Shounen No Jikenbo'' || 2005 || NTV\n|-\n| ''Yakusha Damashii'' || 2006 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| ''Tsubasa No Oreta Tenshitachi 2'' || 2006 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| ''Onna No Ichidaiki SP'' || 2006 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| ''Tokkyu Tanaka San Go'' || 2007 || TBS\n|-\n| ''Jotei'' || 2007 || TV Asahi\n|-\n| ''Change'' || 2008 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| '' [[Oh! My Girl!!]]'' || 2008 || NTV\n|-\n| {{Nihongo|''Ketsuekigatabetsu Onna ga Kekkon Suru Hoho''|\u8840\u6db2\u578b\u5225\u30aa\u30f3\u30ca\u304c\u7d50\u5a5a\u3059\u308b\u65b9\u6cd5}} || 2009 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| ''Door To Door'' || 2009 || TBS\n|-\n| {{Nihongo|''Samayoi Zakura''|\u30b5\u30de\u30e8\u30a4\u30b6\u30af\u30e9}} || 2009 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| {{Nihongo|''Koishite Akuma''|\u604b\u3057\u3066\u60aa\u9b54}} || 2009 || Fuji TV\n|-\n|''Pro Golfer Hana'' || 2010 || NTV\n|-\n| ''Fuyu no Sakura'' || 2011 || TBS\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n50th Television Drama Academy Awards: Best Newcomer (''Dance Drill'')\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080327215359/http://www.ken-on.co.jp/rosa/ Official site] {{in lang|ja}}\n* [http://www.nipponcinema.com/tag/rosa-kato/ Rosa Kato in Nippon Cinema] {{in lang|en}}\n* {{IMDb name|2226713}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kato, Rosa}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Japanese female models]]\n[[Category:Japanese people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Naples]]\n[[Category:People from Kagoshima]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses of Italian descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=July 2011}}\n{{Update|date=July 2016}}\n}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name = Rosa Kato\n| image =\n| imagesize =\n| alt =\n| caption =\n| birth_name = Rosa Kato\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1985|06|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Kagoshima]], Japan\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| other_names = Rosa Matsui (married)\n| occupation = [[Actress]], [[model (person)|model]]\n| yearsactive = 2001&ndash;present\n| spouse = [[Daisuke Matsui]] (22 June 2011&ndash;present)\n| children = 2\n| domesticpartner =\n| website = {{URL|www.ken-on.co.jp/rosa/}}\n}}\n\n{{Nihongo|'''Rosa Kato'''|\u52a0\u85e4 \u30ed\u30fc\u30b5|Kat\u014d R\u014dsa|born 22 June 1985}} is a Japanese [[actress]] and [[commercial model]].\n\n==Biography==\n===Career===\nFrom April 2004 to March 2005, Kato was a regular guest student on ''Italian Conversation'',<ref>[http://www.nhk.or.jp/gogaku/italian/tv/index.html NHK Italian TV Conversation]</ref> a 25-minute [[NHK]] TV program for beginners of Italian. She subsequently began appearing in commercials and became a popular model after appearing in ''Zexy'', a Japanese [[bridal]] magazine, in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.news-postseven.com/archives/20110703_24906.html|title=NEWS\u30dd\u30b9\u30c8\u30bb\u30d6\u30f3\uff5c\u52a0\u85e4\u30ed\u30fc\u30b5\u306e\u610f\u5916\u3068\u300c\u30ae\u30e3\u30eb\u300d\u306a\u7d20\u9854\u306b\u30b7\u30e7\u30c3\u30af\u53d7\u3051\u308b\u4eba\u591a\u6570|publisher=News-postseven.com|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nShe appeared in the Japanese film ''Tokyo Tower'' with [[Jun Matsumoto]] in 2005. In late 2005, she began appearing in [[Japanese television dramas]] such as ''Kindaichi Shonen no Jikenbo''. She later won the \"Best Newcomer Award\" for her performance in ''Dance Drill'' (also known as ''Dandori'' in Japan) in 2006.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvdrama-db.com/drama_info/p/id-39242 |title=\u30c0\u30f3\u30c9\u30ea\u3002 - \u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u8a73\u7d30\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf - \u25c7\u30c6\u30ec\u30d3\u30c9\u30e9\u30de\u30c7\u30fc\u30bf\u30d9\u30fc\u30b9\u25c7|publisher=Tvdrama-db.com|accessdate=5 August 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, she starred in the Japanese drama ''Jotei'' with [[Hana Yori Dango]] actor [[Shota Matsuda]]. In 2008, Kato appeared in several TV dramas such as ''Oh! My Girl!'' with [[Mokomichi Hayami]] and ''Change'' with [[Takuya Kimura]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n\n===Early life===\nKato's mother was [[Japanese people|Japanese]] and her father was [[Italians|Italian]] they met at an Italian restaurant her father worked at in [[Yokohama]]. When Rosa was five years old, the family moved to [[Naples]], Italy. At that time she was able to speak and understand Italian, but has since forgotten almost every word. Hence, Kato was a regular guest student on Italian Conversation [[NHK]] TV program.<ref>[http://www.nhk.or.jp/gogaku/italian/tv/index.html NHK Italian TV Conversation], nhk.or.jp; accessed 20 June 2016.</ref> She was named Rosa after her paternal grandmother.<ref>[http://www.nipponcinema.com/tag/rosa-kato Rosa Kato in Nippon Cinema], nipponcinema.com; accessed 20 June 2016. {{in lang|en}}</ref>\n\n===Personal life===\nOn 22 June 2011, Kato's 26th birthday, she married Japanese football player [[Daisuke Matsui]].<ref>[http://www.houseofjapan.com/movies/matsui-marries-actress-kato \"Matsui marries actress Kato\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120317114420/http://www.houseofjapan.com/movies/matsui-marries-actress-kato |date=2012-03-17 }}, houseofjapan.com; 23 June 2011; retrieved 3 July 2011.</ref> The next day, she announced on her blog her four-month pregnancy with their first child.<ref>[http://www.tokyohive.com/2011/06/kato-rosa-marries-soccer-player-matsui-daisuke-4-months-pregnant Kato Rosa marries soccer player Matsui Daisuke & is 4 months pregnant!] 22 June 2011; retrieved 3 July 2011.</ref> She later gave birth to a son.<ref>{{cite web|author=Staff|url=http://www.ken-on.co.jp/2011/12/post_181.html|title=\u52a0\u85e4\u30ed\u30fc\u30b5\u3088\u308a\u30d5\u30a1\u30f3\u306e\u7686\u3055\u307e\u3078|publisher=KEN-ON|date=14 December 2011|accessdate=5 August 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120613012212/http://www.ken-on.co.jp/2011/12/post_181.html|archivedate=13 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Films ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Title\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2005\n|''[[Tokyo Tower (film)|Tokyo Tower]]''\n|-\n|''Simsons''\n|-\n|''A Day Beyond The Horizon: Itsuka Nami no Kanata ni''\n|-\n|rowspan=5|2006\n|''Catch A Wave''\n|-\n|''Youki na Gang ga Chikyuu wo Mawasu''\n|-\n|''Ichiban Kirei na Mizu''\n|-\n|''Yoru no Pikunikku (Night Time Picnic)''\n|-\n|''Taki 183''\n|-\n|rowspan=3|2007\n|''Unfair: The Movie''\n|-\n|''Smile Seiya no Kiseki''\n|-\n|''Pok\u00e9mon 10th Movie: Dialga Vs. Palkia Vs. Darkrai''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2008\n|''[[Detroit Metal City#Film|Detroit Metal City]]''\n|-\n|''Tengoku wa Mada Tooku''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2012\n|''Girls For Keeps (Garu)''\n|}\n\n=== TV dramas ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Title !! Year !! Network\n|-\n| ''Division 1 - Yuku Na Ryoma!'' || 2005 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| ''Kindaichi Shounen No Jikenbo'' || 2005 || NTV\n|-\n| ''Yakusha Damashii'' || 2006 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| ''Tsubasa No Oreta Tenshitachi 2'' || 2006 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| ''Onna No Ichidaiki SP'' || 2006 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| ''Tokkyu Tanaka San Go'' || 2007 || TBS\n|-\n| ''Jotei'' || 2007 || TV Asahi\n|-\n| ''Change'' || 2008 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| '' [[Oh! My Girl!!]]'' || 2008 || NTV\n|-\n| {{Nihongo|''Ketsuekigatabetsu Onna ga Kekkon Suru Hoho''|\u8840\u6db2\u578b\u5225\u30aa\u30f3\u30ca\u304c\u7d50\u5a5a\u3059\u308b\u65b9\u6cd5}} || 2009 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| ''Door To Door'' || 2009 || TBS\n|-\n| {{Nihongo|''Samayoi Zakura''|\u30b5\u30de\u30e8\u30a4\u30b6\u30af\u30e9}} || 2009 || Fuji TV\n|-\n| {{Nihongo|''Koishite Akuma''|\u604b\u3057\u3066\u60aa\u9b54}} || 2009 || Fuji TV\n|-\n|''Pro Golfer Hana'' || 2010 || NTV\n|-\n| ''Fuyu no Sakura'' || 2011 || TBS\n|}\n\n==Awards==\n50th Television Drama Academy Awards: Best Newcomer (''Dance Drill'')\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080327215359/http://www.ken-on.co.jp/rosa/ Official site] {{in lang|ja}}\n* [http://www.nipponcinema.com/tag/rosa-kato/ Rosa Kato in Nippon Cinema] {{in lang|en}}\n* {{IMDb name|2226713}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kato, Rosa}}\n[[Category:1985 births]]\n[[Category:Japanese female models]]\n[[Category:Japanese people of Italian descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Naples]]\n[[Category:People from Kagoshima]]\n[[Category:21st-century Japanese actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses of Italian descent]]\n", "name_user": "Debiit", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rosa_Kato"}
{"title_page": "Xwedodah", "text_new": "{{Zoroastrianism}}\n'''Xwedodah''' ({{lang-fa|\u062e\u0648\u06cc\u062f\u0648\u062f\u0647}} ; khw\u0113d\u014ddah ; x\u1d5bae\u00aftuuada\u03b8a) is one of the most important religious doctrines in [[Zoroastrianism]] where one marries their close relatives, also known as brother-sister incest marriages or nuclear family incest.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Scheidel|first=Walter|date=1996-09-01|title=Brother-sister and parent-child marriage outside royal families in ancient egypt and iran: A challenge to the sociobiological view of incest avoidance?|journal=Ethology and Sociobiology|language=en|volume=17|issue=5|pages=319\u2013340|doi=10.1016/S0162-3095(96)00074-X|issn=0162-3095}}</ref> It is the highest act of worship in Zoroastrianism, and there are punishments for not preforming it.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/sexuality-in-the-babylonian-talmud/pahlavi-doctrine-of-xwedodah/F04DFC08C8E1F3AFE674002E2509780C|title=The Pahlavi Doctrine of Xw\u0113d\u014ddah|last=Kiel|first=Yishai|date=2016/10|website=Sexuality in the Babylonian Talmud: Christian and Sasanian Contexts in Late Antiquity|language=en|doi=10.1017/cbo9781316658802.007|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> This form of direct familial incest marriage allowed Zoroastrians to marry their sisters, daughters, granddaughters, and their own mothers to take as wives.<ref>Drijvers, H.J.W. ''The Book of the Laws of Countries: Dialogue on Fate of Bardaisan of Edessa'', Assen: Van Gorcum, 1965. pp 43-45</ref>\n==Etymology==\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2020}}\nThe earliest use of the word Xwedodah in Middle Persian in the inscription Kordir on the [[Ka'ba-ye Zartosht]] is in the role of [[Naqsh-e Rostam]].<ref name=\":5\" /> New Avestan texts are x\u1d5ba\u0113tuuada\u03b8a (male) and x\u1d5ba\u0113tuuadai\u03b8\u012b (female) and the adjectives x\u1d5ba\u0113tuuada\u03b8a and x\u1d5ba\u0113tuuada\u03b8\u0101 (female). The nineteenth-century qa\u00eatvadatha style (with q instead of Avesta x) and similar writings reappear in modern literature.\n\nThe first part of the compound seems to be a \"family\" (or similar) of Khito (x\u1d5ba\u0113tu), which is generally thought to derive from the \"self\" (x\u1d5ba\u0113-) with the suffix -you (-tu-), although this is not entirely straightforward . The second part, vada\u03b8a, is nowadays generally regarded as a derivative of the verb (From * Wad-) 'resulting in marriage', related to other Iranian and Hindu European languages which refer to marriage or marriage partner (compare with ancient Indik). \"Wife\" Av. Va\u03b4\u016b; Pahlavi way\u016bg (Pers. Bayu) \"bride\"; Avestan va\u03b4ut \"one who has reached the age of marriage\"; Pahlavi way\u016bdag \"bride's room\"; \n\nThis etymology was suggested by Carl Goldner, and accepted by [[\u00c9mile Benveniste]] and Christian Bartholomae, and became a popular opinion among Western scholars. However, there is no * vadha- to Vedic or * vada- root in the Avesta of the vadh root; in Avesta the v\u0101\u03b4aya and upa.v\u0101\u03b4aiia- 'lead (to marry)' and uzuu\u0101\u03b4aiia are 'leaving the father's house'. vadh-Vedic, vad-Avestan should not be confused with vah-Avestan \"to take\", vaz-Avestan with the uhy\u00e1-unknown form.\n\n== Zoroastrian religious views ==\nMost of Pahlavi's texts are self-contained by [[Edward William West]]'s comments. Brief evaluations and references include Friedrich Spiegel and standard books on Zoroastrianism (such as Boyce).\n\n=== Mythology ===\nIn Zoroastrianism creationism, the world was created through xwedodah.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8, \u201cNext-of-Kin Marriage\u201d; Williams (ed.), The Pahlavi Rivayat, ii, 132\u2013133, n. 4.</ref> When [[Ahura Mazda]] had sex with his daughter [[Spandarmad]], [[Gayomard]] the first human being was created.<ref>Denkard 3.80.4\u20136 (Dresden [ed.], Denkart, 53\u201354; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 73; Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8 [trans.], Spirit of Zoroastrianism, 203); Pahlavi Rivayat 8a (Williams [ed.], The Pahlavi Rivayat, i, 48\u201351, ii, 10\u201311).</ref> Then Gaymard had sex with his mother Spandarmad, and created [[Mashya and Mashyana]].<ref>Denkard 3.80.7 (Dresden [ed.], De\u00afnkart, 54; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 74; Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8 [trans.], Spirit of Zoroastrianism, 203).</ref> Then the siblings Mashya and Mashyana had sex with each other and created the rest of the human race. Zoroastrians believe because the gods had incest with each other, so should humans.<ref>Pahlavi Rivayat 8a6\u20138 (Williams [ed.], The Pahlavi Rivayat, i, 48\u201349, ii, 10); Dadestan \u0131 Den\u0131g 36.69 (Jaafari-Dehaghi [ed.], Dadestan \u0131 Den\u0131g, 136\u2013137); Denkard 7.1.9\u201310 (Dresden [ed.], Denkart, 471; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 592\u2013593).</ref><blockquote>Ohrmazd said: \u201cO Zarathustra, the best thing to have been introduced by/to mankind would have been this, [that] if, since the primal creation, when Mas\u0131 and Masyan\u0131 practiced thus, you would also have practiced thus. Since, when mankind altered that thing, if they had not altered it, just as Mas\u0131 and Masyan\u0131 practiced xwedodah, people would have practiced [it] in that manner.\u201d<ref>Pahlavi Rivayat 8a6\u20138 (cf. Williams [ed.], The Pahlavi Rivayat, i, 48\u201349, ii, 10). Cf. Dadestan \u0131 Den\u0131g 36.69 (Jaafari-Dehaghi [ed.], Dadestan \u0131 Den\u0131g 136\u2013137); De\u00afnkard 7.1.9\u201310 (Dresden [ed.], Denkart, 471; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 592\u2013593).</ref> Masi and Masyani, desiring offspring, had intercourse in the manner of males and females and produced children, which is called the xwedo dah of brother and sister. A great family (dudag) was born from them, who, having paired up, became husbands and wives. And, so, all humans who have been or are came from the original seed (tohm) of xwedodah.<ref>Denkard 3.80.8 (Dresden [ed.], Denkart, 54; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 74; Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8 [trans.], Spirit of Zoroastrianism, 204). See also De\u00afnkard 7.1.10  (Dresden [ed.], De\u00afnkart, 471; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 592\u2013593; Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8 [trans.], Spirit of Zoroastrianism, 111):</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Nuclear family incest ===\nXwedodah is considered the highest act of worship. A man could marry his sister, daughter, or mother in this system.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Forrest, Satnam Mendoza.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/703621262|title=Witches, whores, and sorcerers : the concept of evil in early Iran|date=2011|publisher=University of Texas Press|others=Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8, Prods O.|isbn=978-0-292-72687-1|edition=1st ed|location=Austin|oclc=703621262}}</ref> Zoroastrian religious text provide unequivocal evidence for the desirability and occurrence of nuclear family incest in order to \"preserve the purity of the race, to increase the compatibility of husband and wife, and to increase affection for children\"<ref name=\":1\">de Menasce, J. Le troisime livre du Denkart, Paris: Klincksieck, 1973. Denkard 3.82</ref><ref>Gignoux, P., and Tafazzoli, A. ''Anthologie de Zddspram: Edition Critique du Texte Pehlevi'', Paris: Assocation pour l'Avancement des Etudes Iraniennes, 1993. Selections of Zad-Spram 26.3</ref> Pahlavi Riv\u0101yat 8.a1\u2013c1 explains that the first pair of humans was brother and sister, so they naturally engaged in brother-sister incest, and the original sexual act, the very first act of sex, was between [[Ahura Mazda|Ahura Mazd\u0101]] and his daughter \u0100rmaiti.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNuclear family incest is painted in positive light in Zoroastrian religious text\n\n<blockquote>\"blessed is he who has a child of his child (...) pleasure, sweetness, and joy are owing to a son that a man begets from a daughter of his own, who is also a brother of that same mother; and he who is born of a son and mother is also a brother of that same father; this is a way of much pleasure, which is a blessing of the joy (...) the family is more perfect; its nature is without vexation and gathering affection\"<ref name=\":1\" /></blockquote>\n\nBrother-sister incest is also said to have magical properties, it is written in Rivayat Accompanying the Dadestan I Denig:\n\n<blockquote>For it is revealed that the first time a man has intercourse, 1,000 demons and 2,000 sorcerers and witches die; the second time 2,000 demons and 4,000 sorcerers and witches die; the third time 3,000 demons and 6,000 sorcerers and witches die; the fourth time both man and woman become manifestly blessed.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>\n\nThe most preferred form of xwedodah is an incestuous relationship between a man and his mother as this is seen as the the most closest relationship.<blockquote>he who performs khw\u0113d\u014ddah with one\u2019s birth mother, daughter, or sister. And the greatest, best, and foremost of those four is he who performs khw\u0113d\u014ddah. So wonderful is khw\u0113d\u014ddah.<ref name=\":3\">Pahlavi riv\u0101yat 8c.1\u20136, d.1\u20132</ref></blockquote>The importance of brother-sister incest is emphasized in Zoroastrianism as part of important family bonds as it maintains purity and promotes love.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Zoroastrians also believed that a woman's virginity belonged to her brother or her father first, and they had the right to take it first before she got married, assuming she got married to someone outside the family. The hymen is suppose to be broken by either a woman's brother or her father, as this is property of the family, and it would be considered shameful if it was broken by or her virginity was in possession of a stranger or a foreign enemy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ebrahimnejad|first=Hormoz|date=2015-11-02|title=A Social History of Sexual Relations in Iran|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/00210862.2014.993533|journal=Iranian Studies|volume=48|issue=6|pages=967\u2013970|doi=10.1080/00210862.2014.993533|issn=0021-0862}}</ref> A family would therefore never have to see their daughter being married off to other tribes.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nThere are also punishments for not preforming xwedodah or refusing to engage in it.<ref name=\":5\" /> In the Zoroastrian version of Dante's Inferno, Book of Arda Wiraz 49, where a visitor to hell esquires about the sin committed by a woman entangled in a serpent that crawls into her mouth is given the explanation, \"This is the soul of that wicked woman who violated the next-of-kin marriage\" (who, in other words, refused to have sex with her father, brother, or son and therefore wound up in hell) <ref>Vahman, F. Arda Wiraz Namag: ''The Iranian \"'Divina Commedia,\"'' London and Malmo: Curzon Press, 1986. p 215</ref> This is similar to modern day Shiaism in Iran where the practice of [[Nikah mut'ah|mutah]] (temporary marriage) is also said to have magical divine properties and is effective against sorcery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mahajjah.com/virtues-of-mutah/|title=Virtues of Mut'ah \u2013 Mahajjah|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> One way of destroying huge numbers of sorcerers and witches is by having intercourse with one\u2019s closest relatives.<ref name=\":2\" /><blockquote>S\u014dsh\u0101ns comes, all mankind will practice khw\u0113d\u014ddah, and all the lie- demons will be destroyed by the wonder and power of khw\u0113d\u014ddah.<ref name=\":3\" /></blockquote>The urine of a man or a woman in a incestuous relationship can also be used in purification rituals, such as an [[exorcism]] as is narrated in [[Vendidad]]<ref name=\":2\" /><blockquote>Then Ahura Mazd\u0101 said: Of small or of large domestic animals, but not of men and women, except those two who are men and women in next- of- kin unions. These should make urine with which these corpse- cutters can wash their hair and bodies.<ref>Videvdad 8.13</ref></blockquote>Nuclear family incest was more than a mere religious ideal or rare ritual. Unlike incest in Egypt, or Rome, or Medieval European royalty, this form of nuclear family incest was not relegated to just royalty but was widely popular among all facets of society from slaves, to free men, to the middle class, aristocrats and royalty. Nuclear family incest resulting in progeny was a far cry from an exclusively or even predominantly royal custom.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Non-Persian Sources==\nPersians who immigrated from their homeland in Persia and live across various nations practiced brother-sister incest marriages, and in historical sources are refereed to as Magians, or Majoosi as called by the Arab dialects.<ref name=\":0\" /> There are 60 outside sources referencing Zoroastrian Persian brother-sister incest marriages come from the Greeks, Romans, Armenians, Arabians, Indians, Tibetans, and Chinese, ranging from the 5th century B.C. into the 15th century A.D, roughly 2000 years.<ref name=\":0\" /> Due to the method of Islamic conquests, where newly conquered territory would be allowed to keep their customs and practices as long as they submitted and paid their taxes<ref name=\":4\">Choksy, J.K. ''Zoroastrians in Muslim lran: selected problems of coexistence and interaction during the early medieval period.'' Iranian Studies 20:17-30, 1987.</ref> This was to maintain stability over a multicultural empire, and thus Zoroastrian brother-sister incest continued to persist and exist well into the Middle Ages.<ref>Sachau, E. ''Syrische Rechtsbiicher'', 3, Berlin: Georg Reimer, 1914.</ref>\n\n=== Islamic ===\nMuslim writers have cited this tradition. For example, [[Al-Tha'alibi]] writes that Zoroastrian legalized marriage between brothers and sisters and fathers and daughters because Adam had married his sons to his daughters. [[Al-Masudi]] cites Zoroastrian incest and reports that [[Ardashir I]] told his people to marry close relatives to strengthen family ties. [[Ferdowsi]] mentions incest between Bahman and his sister Homa.<ref name=\"iranicaonline.org\">http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/marriage-next-of-kin</ref>\n\n=== Jewish ===\nJewish philosopher [[Philo]] has mentioned the marriage of high-ranking Iranians to their mothers and the high status of the children of these links.\n\n=== Christian ===\nThe most comprehensive reports come from [[Eastern Christianity|Eastern Christians]] who lived under Persian rule, they wrote down that these were not just fictitious stories of far away people, but were indeed very real and widely practiced. Iso'bokht, the [[Church of the East|Nestorian]] patriarch of the [[Persis]] writes many books on this topic urging Christians and other peoples to not practice this custom.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n===Greek===\nThe common feature of non-Iranian sources is that they rarely mention the Iranians themselves, even if they do occasionally mention the [[majus]] clerics. Numerous classical sources and later authors point to the incarnation of incest in the [[Achaemenid Empire|Achaemenid]] monarchies of the [[Parthian]] and [[Sasanian Empire|Sassanian]] dynasties. Some of the earliest Greek references to non-royal incest are those by [[Xanthus (historian)|Xanthus]] in his book Magica, which [[Clement of Alexandria]] quoted as saying that [[Magi]] had sex with their mothers, daughters and sisters, and that [[Ctesias]] had mentioned a brother-sister marriage. [[Herodotus]] mentions that Cambyses lived with his sister, though the Persians had never been with their sisters before.<ref name=\"iranicaonline.org\" />\n\n=== Chinese ===\nA reference can be found in the Pahlavi-Chinese bilingual tomb inscriptions in Xi'an, in which the deceased woman, from the Surin family princes, is read in Chinese as \"wife\" but in Pahlavi's \"daughter\".\n\n==See also==\n*[[Persian wedding]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Marriage, unions and partnerships in Iran]]\n[[Category:Incest]]\n[[Category:Zoroastrian behaviour and experience]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|{{refimprove|date=January 2020}}}}\n{{Zoroastrianism}}\n'''Xwedodah''' ({{lang-fa|\u062e\u0648\u06cc\u062f\u0648\u062f\u0647}} ; khw\u0113d\u014ddah ; x\u1d5bae\u00aftuuada\u03b8a) is one of the most important religious doctrines in [[Zoroastrianism]] where one marries their close relatives, also known as brother-sister incest marriages or nuclear family incest.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite journal|last=Scheidel|first=Walter|date=1996-09-01|title=Brother-sister and parent-child marriage outside royal families in ancient egypt and iran: A challenge to the sociobiological view of incest avoidance?|journal=Ethology and Sociobiology|language=en|volume=17|issue=5|pages=319\u2013340|doi=10.1016/S0162-3095(96)00074-X|issn=0162-3095}}</ref> It is the highest act of worship in Zoroastrianism, and there are punishments for not preforming it.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cambridge.org/core/books/sexuality-in-the-babylonian-talmud/pahlavi-doctrine-of-xwedodah/F04DFC08C8E1F3AFE674002E2509780C|title=The Pahlavi Doctrine of Xw\u0113d\u014ddah|last=Kiel|first=Yishai|date=2016/10|website=Sexuality in the Babylonian Talmud: Christian and Sasanian Contexts in Late Antiquity|language=en|doi=10.1017/cbo9781316658802.007|access-date=2020-04-19}}</ref> This form of direct familial incest marriage allowed Zoroastrians to marry their sisters, daughters, granddaughters, and their own mothers to take as wives.<ref>Drijvers, H.J.W. ''The Book of the Laws of Countries: Dialogue on Fate of Bardaisan of Edessa'', Assen: Van Gorcum, 1965. pp 43-45</ref>\n==Etymology==\nThe earliest use of the word Xwedodah in Middle Persian in the inscription Kordir on the [[Ka'ba-ye Zartosht]] is in the role of [[Naqsh-e Rostam]].<ref name=\":5\" /> New Avestan texts are x\u1d5ba\u0113tuuada\u03b8a (male) and x\u1d5ba\u0113tuuadai\u03b8\u012b (female) and the adjectives x\u1d5ba\u0113tuuada\u03b8a and x\u1d5ba\u0113tuuada\u03b8\u0101 (female). The nineteenth-century qa\u00eatvadatha style (with q instead of Avesta x) and similar writings reappear in modern literature.\n\nThe first part of the compound seems to be a \"family\" (or similar) of Khito (x\u1d5ba\u0113tu), which is generally thought to derive from the \"self\" (x\u1d5ba\u0113-) with the suffix -you (-tu-), although this is not entirely straightforward . The second part, vada\u03b8a, is nowadays generally regarded as a derivative of the verb (From * Wad-) 'resulting in marriage', related to other Iranian and Hindu European languages which refer to marriage or marriage partner (compare with ancient Indik). \"Wife\" Av. Va\u03b4\u016b; Pahlavi way\u016bg (Pers. Bayu) \"bride\"; Avestan va\u03b4ut \"one who has reached the age of marriage\"; Pahlavi way\u016bdag \"bride's room\"; \n\nThis etymology was suggested by Carl Goldner, and accepted by [[\u00c9mile Benveniste]] and Christian Bartholomae, and became a popular opinion among Western scholars. However, there is no * vadha- to Vedic or * vada- root in the Avesta of the vadh root; in Avesta the v\u0101\u03b4aya and upa.v\u0101\u03b4aiia- 'lead (to marry)' and uzuu\u0101\u03b4aiia are 'leaving the father's house'. vadh-Vedic, vad-Avestan should not be confused with vah-Avestan \"to take\", vaz-Avestan with the uhy\u00e1-unknown form.\n\n== Zoroastrian religious views ==\nMost of Pahlavi's texts are self-contained by [[Edward William West]]'s comments. Brief evaluations and references include Friedrich Spiegel and standard books on Zoroastrianism (such as Boyce).\n\n=== Mythology ===\nIn Zoroastrianism creationism, the world was created through xwedodah.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8, \u201cNext-of-Kin Marriage\u201d; Williams (ed.), The Pahlavi Rivayat, ii, 132\u2013133, n. 4.</ref> When [[Ahura Mazda]] had sex with his daughter [[Spandarmad]], [[Gayomard]] the first human being was created.<ref>Denkard 3.80.4\u20136 (Dresden [ed.], Denkart, 53\u201354; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 73; Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8 [trans.], Spirit of Zoroastrianism, 203); Pahlavi Rivayat 8a (Williams [ed.], The Pahlavi Rivayat, i, 48\u201351, ii, 10\u201311).</ref> Then Gaymard had sex with his mother Spandarmad, and created [[Mashya and Mashyana]].<ref>Denkard 3.80.7 (Dresden [ed.], De\u00afnkart, 54; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 74; Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8 [trans.], Spirit of Zoroastrianism, 203).</ref> Then the siblings Mashya and Mashyana had sex with each other and created the rest of the human race. Zoroastrians believe because the gods had incest with each other, so should humans.<ref>Pahlavi Rivayat 8a6\u20138 (Williams [ed.], The Pahlavi Rivayat, i, 48\u201349, ii, 10); Dadestan \u0131 Den\u0131g 36.69 (Jaafari-Dehaghi [ed.], Dadestan \u0131 Den\u0131g, 136\u2013137); Denkard 7.1.9\u201310 (Dresden [ed.], Denkart, 471; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 592\u2013593).</ref><blockquote>Ohrmazd said: \u201cO Zarathustra, the best thing to have been introduced by/to mankind would have been this, [that] if, since the primal creation, when Mas\u0131 and Masyan\u0131 practiced thus, you would also have practiced thus. Since, when mankind altered that thing, if they had not altered it, just as Mas\u0131 and Masyan\u0131 practiced xwedodah, people would have practiced [it] in that manner.\u201d<ref>Pahlavi Rivayat 8a6\u20138 (cf. Williams [ed.], The Pahlavi Rivayat, i, 48\u201349, ii, 10). Cf. Dadestan \u0131 Den\u0131g 36.69 (Jaafari-Dehaghi [ed.], Dadestan \u0131 Den\u0131g 136\u2013137); De\u00afnkard 7.1.9\u201310 (Dresden [ed.], Denkart, 471; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 592\u2013593).</ref> Masi and Masyani, desiring offspring, had intercourse in the manner of males and females and produced children, which is called the xwedo dah of brother and sister. A great family (dudag) was born from them, who, having paired up, became husbands and wives. And, so, all humans who have been or are came from the original seed (tohm) of xwedodah.<ref>Denkard 3.80.8 (Dresden [ed.], Denkart, 54; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 74; Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8 [trans.], Spirit of Zoroastrianism, 204). See also De\u00afnkard 7.1.10  (Dresden [ed.], De\u00afnkart, 471; Madan [ed.], Pahlavi Dinkard, 592\u2013593; Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8 [trans.], Spirit of Zoroastrianism, 111):</ref></blockquote>\n\n=== Nuclear family incest ===\nXwedodah is considered the highest act of worship. A man could marry his sister, daughter, or mother in this system.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Forrest, Satnam Mendoza.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/703621262|title=Witches, whores, and sorcerers : the concept of evil in early Iran|date=2011|publisher=University of Texas Press|others=Skj\u00e6rv\u00f8, Prods O.|isbn=978-0-292-72687-1|edition=1st ed|location=Austin|oclc=703621262}}</ref> Zoroastrian religious text provide unequivocal evidence for the desirability and occurrence of nuclear family incest in order to \"preserve the purity of the race, to increase the compatibility of husband and wife, and to increase affection for children\"<ref name=\":1\">de Menasce, J. Le troisime livre du Denkart, Paris: Klincksieck, 1973. Denkard 3.82</ref><ref>Gignoux, P., and Tafazzoli, A. ''Anthologie de Zddspram: Edition Critique du Texte Pehlevi'', Paris: Assocation pour l'Avancement des Etudes Iraniennes, 1993. Selections of Zad-Spram 26.3</ref> Pahlavi Riv\u0101yat 8.a1\u2013c1 explains that the first pair of humans was brother and sister, so they naturally engaged in brother-sister incest, and the original sexual act, the very first act of sex, was between [[Ahura Mazda|Ahura Mazd\u0101]] and his daughter \u0100rmaiti.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nNuclear family incest is painted in positive light in Zoroastrian religious text\n\n<blockquote>\"blessed is he who has a child of his child (...) pleasure, sweetness, and joy are owing to a son that a man begets from a daughter of his own, who is also a brother of that same mother; and he who is born of a son and mother is also a brother of that same father; this is a way of much pleasure, which is a blessing of the joy (...) the family is more perfect; its nature is without vexation and gathering affection\"<ref name=\":1\" /></blockquote>\n\nBrother-sister incest is also said to have magical properties, it is written in Rivayat Accompanying the Dadestan I Denig:\n\n<blockquote>For it is revealed that the first time a man has intercourse, 1,000 demons and 2,000 sorcerers and witches die; the second time 2,000 demons and 4,000 sorcerers and witches die; the third time 3,000 demons and 6,000 sorcerers and witches die; the fourth time both man and woman become manifestly blessed.<ref name=\":0\" /></blockquote>\n\nThe most preferred form of xwedodah is an incestuous relationship between a man and his mother as this is seen as the the most closest relationship.<blockquote>he who performs khw\u0113d\u014ddah with one\u2019s birth mother, daughter, or sister. And the greatest, best, and foremost of those four is he who performs khw\u0113d\u014ddah. So wonderful is khw\u0113d\u014ddah.<ref name=\":3\">Pahlavi riv\u0101yat 8c.1\u20136, d.1\u20132</ref></blockquote>The importance of brother-sister incest is emphasized in Zoroastrianism as part of important family bonds as it maintains purity and promotes love.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":5\" /> Zoroastrians also believed that a woman's virginity belonged to her brother or her father first, and they had the right to take it first before she got married, assuming she got married to someone outside the family. The hymen is suppose to be broken by either a woman's brother or her father, as this is property of the family, and it would be considered shameful if it was broken by or her virginity was in possession of a stranger or a foreign enemy.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ebrahimnejad|first=Hormoz|date=2015-11-02|title=A Social History of Sexual Relations in Iran|url=https://doi.org/10.1080/00210862.2014.993533|journal=Iranian Studies|volume=48|issue=6|pages=967\u2013970|doi=10.1080/00210862.2014.993533|issn=0021-0862}}</ref> A family would therefore never have to see their daughter being married off to other tribes.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nThere are also punishments for not preforming xwedodah or refusing to engage in it.<ref name=\":5\" /> In the Zoroastrian version of Dante's Inferno, Book of Arda Wiraz 49, where a visitor to hell esquires about the sin committed by a woman entangled in a serpent that crawls into her mouth is given the explanation, \"This is the soul of that wicked woman who violated the next-of-kin marriage\" (who, in other words, refused to have sex with her father, brother, or son and therefore wound up in hell) <ref>Vahman, F. Arda Wiraz Namag: ''The Iranian \"'Divina Commedia,\"'' London and Malmo: Curzon Press, 1986. p 215</ref> This is similar to modern day Shiaism in Iran where the practice of [[Nikah mut'ah|mutah]] (temporary marriage) is also said to have magical divine properties and is effective against sorcery.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mahajjah.com/virtues-of-mutah/|title=Virtues of Mut'ah \u2013 Mahajjah|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-24}}</ref> One way of destroying huge numbers of sorcerers and witches is by having intercourse with one\u2019s closest relatives.<ref name=\":2\" /><blockquote>S\u014dsh\u0101ns comes, all mankind will practice khw\u0113d\u014ddah, and all the lie- demons will be destroyed by the wonder and power of khw\u0113d\u014ddah.<ref name=\":3\" /></blockquote>The urine of a man or a woman in a incestuous relationship can also be used in purification rituals, such as an [[exorcism]] as is narrated in [[Vendidad]]<ref name=\":2\" /><blockquote>Then Ahura Mazd\u0101 said: Of small or of large domestic animals, but not of men and women, except those two who are men and women in next- of- kin unions. These should make urine with which these corpse- cutters can wash their hair and bodies.<ref>Videvdad 8.13</ref></blockquote>Nuclear family incest was more than a mere religious ideal or rare ritual. Unlike incest in Egypt, or Rome, or Medieval European royalty, this form of nuclear family incest was not relegated to just royalty but was widely popular among all facets of society from slaves, to free men, to the middle class, aristocrats and royalty. Nuclear family incest resulting in progeny was a far cry from an exclusively or even predominantly royal custom.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Non-Persian Sources==\nPersians who immigrated from their homeland in Persia and live across various nations practiced brother-sister incest marriages, and in historical sources are refereed to as Magians, or Majoosi as called by the Arab dialects.<ref name=\":0\" /> There are 60 outside sources referencing Zoroastrian Persian brother-sister incest marriages come from the Greeks, Romans, Armenians, Arabians, Indians, Tibetans, and Chinese, ranging from the 5th century B.C. into the 15th century A.D, roughly 2000 years.<ref name=\":0\" /> Due to the method of Islamic conquests, where newly conquered territory would be allowed to keep their customs and practices as long as they submitted and paid their taxes<ref name=\":4\">Choksy, J.K. ''Zoroastrians in Muslim lran: selected problems of coexistence and interaction during the early medieval period.'' Iranian Studies 20:17-30, 1987.</ref> This was to maintain stability over a multicultural empire, and thus Zoroastrian brother-sister incest continued to persist and exist well into the Middle Ages.<ref>Sachau, E. ''Syrische Rechtsbiicher'', 3, Berlin: Georg Reimer, 1914.</ref>\n\n=== Islamic ===\nMuslim writers have cited this tradition. For example, [[Al-Tha'alibi]] writes that Zoroastrian legalized marriage between brothers and sisters and fathers and daughters because Adam had married his sons to his daughters. [[Al-Masudi]] cites Zoroastrian incest and reports that [[Ardashir I]] told his people to marry close relatives to strengthen family ties. [[Ferdowsi]] mentions incest between Bahman and his sister Homa.<ref name=\"iranicaonline.org\">http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/marriage-next-of-kin</ref>\n\n=== Jewish ===\nJewish philosopher [[Philo]] has mentioned the marriage of high-ranking Iranians to their mothers and the high status of the children of these links.\n\n=== Christian ===\nThe most comprehensive reports come from [[Eastern Christianity|Eastern Christians]] who lived under Persian rule, they wrote down that these were not just fictitious stories of far away people, but were indeed very real and widely practiced. Iso'bokht, the [[Church of the East|Nestorian]] patriarch of the [[Persis]] writes many books on this topic urging Christians and other peoples to not practice this custom.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":4\" />\n\n===Greek===\nThe common feature of non-Iranian sources is that they rarely mention the Iranians themselves, even if they do occasionally mention the [[majus]] clerics. Numerous classical sources and later authors point to the incarnation of incest in the [[Achaemenid Empire|Achaemenid]] monarchies of the [[Parthian]] and [[Sasanian Empire|Sassanian]] dynasties. Some of the earliest Greek references to non-royal incest are those by [[Xanthus (historian)|Xanthus]] in his book Magica, which [[Clement of Alexandria]] quoted as saying that [[Magi]] had sex with their mothers, daughters and sisters, and that [[Ctesias]] had mentioned a brother-sister marriage. [[Herodotus]] mentions that Cambyses lived with his sister, though the Persians had never been with their sisters before.<ref name=\"iranicaonline.org\" />\n\n=== Chinese ===\nA reference can be found in the Pahlavi-Chinese bilingual tomb inscriptions in Xi'an, in which the deceased woman, from the Surin family princes, is read in Chinese as \"wife\" but in Pahlavi's \"daughter\".\n\n==See also==\n*[[Persian wedding]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n[[Category:Marriage, unions and partnerships in Iran]]\n[[Category:Incest]]\n[[Category:Zoroastrian behaviour and experience]]\n", "name_user": "Qayrawan", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xwedodah"}
